<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned over Iran's Medium-Range Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The White House Thursday
confirmed newspaper reports that Iran had successfully test-fired
a medium-range missile and expressed its "concern" over the
development of Iran's missile.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the test, detected by
U.S. spy satellites Wednesday, involved a missile known as the
Shehab-3, which has a range of about 800 miles (1,300 km).
</P>
<P>
"We detected the launch," McCurry told reporters, noting that
the United States is "actively monitoring their military
capacity."
</P>
<P>
As the range of the Iranian medium-range missile could cover
all of Israel, Saudi Arabia and part of Turkey, McCurry said, "It
is a source of concern to us."
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said it was a significant development in Iran's
missile "because it puts U.S. forces in the region at risk."
</P>
<P>
Data on the missile test are being evaluated by U.S.
intelligence agencies to determine in more detail its estimated
range, payload capacity and other characteristics, another U.S.
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
