<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Maintain "Non-intervention" policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) agreed here
Thursday night that "non-intervention" will be maintained as the
cardinal policy of the group but interactions will be allowed on
certain issues which have trans-boundary effects.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Thursday night, Philippine
Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said that at an informal working
dinner, ASEAN foreign ministers exchanged views on the proposed
change of ASEAN's policy from "non-intervention" to "flexible
engagement."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the ministers agreed that "in the conduct of
relations among states, the principle of non-intervention in the
domestic affairs of states should be respected."
</P>
<P>
But in view of the changing situation, globalization and
"growing interdependence among nations, particularly among ASEAN
countries, the rule or principle of non-intervention in domestic
affairs of others should not be absolute, but should be relative
particularly on the issues which have trans-boundary effects. And
the ASEAN members should be able to express their views clearly
and timely and openly," Siazon said.
</P>
<P>
"And they (ministers) suggested that this be considered as a
policy of ASEAN," he added.
</P>
<P>
Siazon further explained that on certain issues, such as
transnational crimes and forest fires, other ASEAN members can
express their views.
</P>
<P>
The policy change proposal was made by Thai Foreign Minister
Surin Pitsuwan in a letter sent to Philippine Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon last week. The proposal was backed by the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said earlier that since domestic developments in any
ASEAN member country would have positive or adverse effects on
other members, he and the Thai foreign minister called for "a
change in ASEAN's policy from constructive engagement to flexible
engagement, suggesting a more proactive policy in the affairs of
other ASEAN countries."
</P>
<P>
But most of the ASEAN members are strongly opposed to the
policy change.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN ministers are here to attend the annual ministerial
meeting which starts Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, and the
Philippines is the chairman of this year's ASEAN ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
This year's ASEAN ministerial meeting is expected to discuss
topics including the financial turmoil in the region, ASEAN unity
and cooperation in face of the turmoil, Cambodia, nuclear
proliferation in South Asia and transnational crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
