<HEADLINE> Lesotho High Court Orders Inspection of Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho High Court Thursday
ordered the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) to allow three
main opposition parties to inspect election documents.
</P>
<P>
The order was issued two months after the conclusion of the
Lesotho general elections on May 23, the third since the country
gained independence in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said the Basotholand Congress Party (BCP),
the Basotho National Party (BNP) and the Marematlou Freedom Party
have alleged serious irregularities in the outcome of the
elections which they claimed the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy rigged.
</P>
<P>
The order directed Chairman of the IEC, Sejkara Mafisa,
and the director of elections to make relevant documents
available to an individual upon the completion of inspection
forms.
</P>
<P>
It was also ordered that an individual may be assisted in his
inspection by other persons who may be present with him at the
offices designated by the director of elections.
</P>
<P>
The number of persons inspecting election documents at any one
time must be limited to six, the order said.
</P>
<P>
Both the BCP and the BNP used to be the ruling parties in the
tiny mountain kingdom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4thld Writethru: Tehran Mayor Sentenced to 5 Years' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Tehran's mayor was found guilty of
corruption and sentenced to five years' imprisonment Thursday, an
event widely seen as the spinoff of an intense political struggle.
</P>
<P>
A public court announced that Gholamhussein Karbaschi was
guilty of embezzlement and misappropriation of public fund, also
sentencing him to 60 lashes with a probation of four years.
</P>
<P>
The mayor was banned from holding public office for 20 years
and fined 1 billion rials (about 180,000 U.S. dollars at market
rate).
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi was convicted on collaboration in the sale of a
printing house and machinery and misappropriation of 35,911
million rials (about 6.5 million dollars) of the Tehran
municipality's funds. He was asked to return the unpaid fund of
17,646 million rials (3.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Judge Mohseni Ejaei said that Karbaschi can appeal within 20
days after the verdict was pronounced. He told reporters that
Karbaschi will remain free on bail until the appeal.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi's lawyer Bahman Keshavarz announced on Thursday that
Karbaschi will appeal against the court verdict,
</P>
<P>
Keshavarz said that the court decision was not a surprise and
the defense team had "expected such a verdict," the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi did not appear before the court and was represented
by Keshavarz. More than 200 people, including some 40 domestic and
foreign reporters and photographers crammed the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
In a 39-page ruling read out in more than an hour, the court
repeated all the charges against the mayor and refuted each and
every of his defense.
</P>
<P>
The mayor, a famous reformist and a close ally of President
Mohammad Khatami, was the highest-ranking official charged for
corruption since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The open trial of the mayor, which started on June 7,
highlighted the political struggle between the moderates and
conservatives, pushing political groups and even the media in the
country to line up against each other.
</P>
<P>
The moderates believed the case was politically motivated with
an aim to weaken the government of Khatami, who enjoyed strong
support from Karbaschi and his followers since the presidential
elections in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi financed Khatami's presidential campaign, which
brought about a landslide victory over the conservative candidate,
Majlis (Parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
On April 4, Karbaschi was temporally detained by the
conservative judiciary, but was released 11 days later following
direct interference of the top Iranian leadership.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives vowed to punish any one violating
the country's law and attacked the moderates for abusing freedom
and democracy proposed by Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The new president is trying to push forward social reforms and
has promised to bring changes to people's lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
