<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Price Control to Thwart IMF Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government's
re-introduction of price controls could thwart the release of
further financial aid by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), a
major bankroller of Zimbabwe's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
An IMF official, Michael Nowak Thursday told the Zimbabwe News
Agency in an telephone interview from Washington that officials
from the financial institution would visit Harare early next
month to discuss the issue and the release of 18 million U.S.
Dollars to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The IMF in June released the 53 million U.S. Dollar part of four
tranches to be disbursed under a 176 million U.S. Dollar stand-by
credit facility aimed at improving Zimbabwe' balance of payments
position and kickstart the second phase of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the second tranche of 18 million U.S. Dollars
scheduled for releasing mid-August and subsequent tranches were to
be released subject to the targets set by a government meeting
at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the country had met the targets, Nowak said,
"There is the issue relating to price controls which we would
need to discuss with the government."
</P>
<P>
The government last month reintroduced price controls, saying
this would stop producers of basic food commodities from using
price rises to stir social unrest.
</P>
<P>
The government last January unleashed troops to quell violent
riots sparked by an increase in the price of the staple maize
meal.
</P>
<P>
However, the move has been criticized by economists and
western donors who say it is a negation of economic reforms the
country embarked upon in 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Criticizes U.S. Statements on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus on Thursday slammed what it
called partial statements made by the U.S. government over the
situation in the divided Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Christos Stylianides criticized a
statement made Wednesday by the White House spokesman Mike
McCurry, who described the 1974 event as "a conflict."
</P>
<P>
"It looks he (McCurry) is confused with dates to consider that
in 1974 there was just a conflict and not an invasion,"
Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in 1974 with a claimed aim to protect the Turkish
Cypriots there in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot spokesman said it would be better if the
U.S. official had contacted American citizens, relatives of
missing persons or other victims of the Turkish invasion, "to
realize the difference between an invasion and a conflict."
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned by the American diplomacy and positions
because they appear contradictory in many cases and far from
being objective to what the real facts are," he said.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging the U.S. important role in seeking a
solution to the Cyprus issue, he said, "we should on every
occasion point out the faux pas of American diplomacy and policy."
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides also expressed indignation
at the statements made by U.S. State Department spokesman James
Rubin, who said Tuesday that no Turkish combat aircraft overflew
Nicosia last Monday during the celebrations held in the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled north to mark the 24th anniversary of Turkish
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Rubin only added that Turkish Cypriot Cessnas and helicopters
might have done so and a Turkish air force acrobatics team staged
an air show near northern coastal town of Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the U.S. should be aware that "the airspace of
the Republic of Cyprus, which covers the whole of the island, is
continuously violated and there could be no excuse that the
aircrafts flew here for an air show."
</P>
<P>
Clerides pointed out that "if any aircraft enters the national
airspace of a country without prior permission from the
government, it is violating this airspace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
