<HEADLINE> Israel Expresses Concern Over Reported Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai Thursday expressed concern over a New York
Times report that Iran had tested a medium-range missile.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Mordechai as saying that it is very
serious that Iran could have very fast tested such a weapon.
</P>
<P>
New York Times reported that a U.S. spy satellite detected the
test launch in Iran on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report alleged that Iran bought the missile, which is
capable of reaching Israel, from the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Mordechai noted that the Iranian missile
test does not pose an immediate threat to Israel.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said he doubted that such a missile could
reach Israel, saying a war is unlikely for the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky
told Israel Radio that although the missile tested in Iran might
be brought in from the DPRK, the main source of missile technology
for Iran is in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky said that Israel would take immediate measures to
prevent Iran from developing missiles capable of striking Israel.
</P>
