<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets up Tariff Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
has appointed a three-member tariff commission to investigate
unfair trade practices and tariff charges which threaten the
viability of local industries.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be chaired by Dzikamai Danha, a former
director of the Pan African Institute for Development and the
African Development Bank, Zimbabwean Ministry of Industry and
Commerce announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The commission is an independent advisory body which provides
assistance or protection to local industries threatened by
unequal external trade competition following the removal of
subsidies, import controls and administered foreign currency
allocations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the commission will review and recommend the
adoption of a coherent tariff policy to lower tariff charges on
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
It will also recommend the raising of tariff charges on
imported goods and services that compete with locally produced
goods and services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
