<HEADLINE> Israeli Coalition Whip Calls for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel's coalition whip Meir
Shetrit Thursday called for an Israeli-Palestinian summit to
discuss some "new ideas" he has proposed to Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Arafat in Gaza Thursday, Shetrit raised
the ideas, of which he said Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is aware, Israel Radio reported. Shetrit, the Likud
Member of the Knesset (Parliament) refused to elaborate the ideas,
but he said Arafat promised to study them seriously.
</P>
<P>
He called for a summit meeting between Arafat and Netanyahu
during which his ideas will be discussed. He said disputes between
the Israelis and the Palestinians over the American proposal
calling on Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank
can not be resolved by mediators. "I do hope that (the summit)
will happen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Planning and International Cooperation Minister
Nabil Shaath expressed his appreciation for the "sincere attempt"
of Shetrit to revive the talks, saying the Palestinians will "look
and study seriously" his new ideas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has also called for
an Israeli-Palestinian summit since he met Sunday with Arafat's
deputy Mahmoud Abbas in the first direct talks between the two
sides in months. He said they had gone as far as they could.
</P>
<P>
Following two rounds of negotiations, the Israeli-Palestinian
talks ended abruptly Wednesday. The Palestinians complained that
the Israelis brought no new proposals and the Israelis appealed
for fresh American diplomatic intervention to resume the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians kept the Israelis in the dark Thursday by
saying that they would give an answer in the next 48 hours
as to whether they agree to continue the talks.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Israeli delegation was proposing to
carry out a 10 percent withdrawal and turn the additional 3
percent into "nature reserves," where no construction will be
permitted. But the Palestinians have stressed that the percentages
in the American pullback initiative were "nonnegotiable."
</P>
<P>
Israel has been seeking for a Netanyahu-Arafat summit for
months. The Palestinians have repeatedly rejected the idea, saying
what is needed is Israel's acceptance of the American proposal,
not summit. 
</P>
