<HEADLINE> McCurry to Step Down as White House Press Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
announced Thursday that his press secretary Mike McCurry would
leave in the fall and be replaced by deputy spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
"Much to my regret but with my full understanding and support
Mike McCurry will be leaving us in the fall," Clinton said during
a surprise appearance in the White House press briefing room. "I
have also determined to appoint Joe Lockhart as his successor."
</P>
<P>
The announcement ended months of speculation that McCurry would
depart. He and Lockhart flanked the president as the announcement
was made.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said McCurry "has set the standard" for future
presidential press secretaries.
</P>
<P>
"In an age where Washington has come to be governed by a
24-hour news cycle and endless cable channels with their special
niche audiences, Mike has redefined the job as press secretary in
a new and more challenging ear," Clinton said. "Few could match
his intelligence and wit from the podium."
</P>
<P>
McCurry did not reveal his future plans. He said he would like
to teach and explore options that don't involve being a spokesman,
a duty has has performed in Washington for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to the White House, McCurry was spokesman at the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said he would remain at the White House until Congress
adjourns this year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he considered Lockhart "the ideal replacement" for
McCurry. "Joe knows you well and you know him well, and that's
probably half the battle," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart has worked extensively in political campaigns. Before
joining the Clinton-Gore re-election campaign, Lockhart was a
consultant at the Washington firm Robinson Lerer Sawyer Miller
Inc. He also has worked in broadcasting at ABC and CNN. He left
CNN in 1988 to work for Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
</P>
</TEXT>
