<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano urged the world to keep an open eye on possible harms on
offshore areas by human activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Pan-Africa Conference
on Integration of the Coastal Areas and Sustainable Management,
Chissano said that most of the coastal countries are under the
pressure of population over-growth and environmental
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said that technical, financial and human resources
must be mobilized to face the challenges of deteriorating
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is greatly concerned with the
fragility of its offshore areas, Chissano said, adding that
Mozambique's offshore areas are endangered by erosion, accidents
on the seas, seashore pollution and illegal fishing by
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is trying to set up a central
institution to protect the natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is also mapping out plan for a
sustainable development of the offshore resources, Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
The conference is co-sponsored by Finnish government, the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
and the United Nations Environment Program and Mozambican
government.
</P>
<P>
About 41 environment ministers and representatives from 12
countries attended the conference to be closed on July 25.
</P>
