<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Renews Peace Efforts on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.S. envoy said here
Thursday that he has brought new ideas to help reach a settlement
to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival, Thomas Miller, U.S. State
Department Coordinator for Cyprus, said his visit is part of the
effort to find a solution for the divided island.
</P>
<P>
"I bring ideas but prefer to keep them within the realm of our
close discussions," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, the U.S. envoy is expected to have
separate meetings with the two leaders of the rival Greek and
Turkish communities, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece. The Turkish Cypriots set up a breakaway republic in 1983,
but only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy stressed that the only way to make progress is
through direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the U.S. support for the demilitarization of
Cyprus, that "will take into account the security concerns of all
the people of the island."
</P>
<P>
Referring to attempts to resume the stalled peace effort,
Miller said "when a door is locked, a window is opened and we have
to find that window."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks hit a snag last August after Denktash walked
out of the U.N.-sponsored peace talks with Clerides to protest
against the European Union's decision to start accession talks
with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
However, Miller said that the preconditions the Turkish Cypriot
side set to return to the negotiating table could not be met,
saying they are untenable.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he would not participate the peace talks
unless his breakaway entity in northern Cyprus is recognized and
Cyprus withdraws its application for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Richard Holbrooke, former U.S. Presidential Emissary for
Cyprus, and Miller visited Cyprus last May, but they failed to
bring the two community leaders back to the negotiating table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
