<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Only Prolonged Peace Will Save Sudan's Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- If mass starvation of
children and women is to be averted in south Sudan, the cease-fire
must be adhered to and expanded to ensure that urgent humanitarian
relief can reach people most in need, Carol Bellamy, executive
director of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF chief visited famine-stricken towns in south Sudan
to take a first-hand look at the humanitarian situation on the
ground just days after a cease-fire was announced by the
government of Sudan and the Sudan People's liberation Movement.
</P>
<P>
"The suffering I witnessed in these famine-stricken areas was
horrific. Children, who should be running and playing, have become
mere skeletal figures, too weak to stand and barely able to feed
themselves," Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"Most shocking of all were the rows of freshly dug graves in
the areas, where I was told that 51 children and adults had died
only hours earlier," she said.
</P>
<P>
While the three-month cease-fire is a welcome start, Bellamy
said, what children and their families need most is prolonged
peace encompassing the entire area of southern Sudan. This should
include western Upper Nile where insecurity is having devastating
effects on the delivery of humanitarian assistance as well as on
the lives of the people who live there.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy applauded the efforts of the World Food Program, which
is in the midst of the largest airdrop in its history. She
appealed to the international community to redouble efforts to
help facilitate an urgently-needed political solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
