<HEADLINE> New Plant to Provide Enough Power for Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bujagali power plant on the
Nile River, expected to be commissioned in July 2003, will be the
biggest source of power in Uganda and is projected to produce
enough electricity for the developing country, Radio Uganda
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a power official as saying the same day at a
forum on the future of electric power supply that the new plant,
to be located some 80 kilometers east of Kampala, is to produce
270 megawatts of power, one and a half times that of the Owen
Falls Dam.
</P>
<P>
On the choice of site for the power project, the official said
that the dam will be the cheapest and most environmentally
suitable.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Owen power plant supplies Uganda with
two-thirds of power it needs. It also sells power to the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Previously, there was heated debate on whether the Bujagali
Falls should be developed into a tourist site or a power plant.
Some argued that the place is the best choice for white water
rafting which will not spoil the beautiful environment.
</P>
<P>
Others, however, said Uganda, which is gaining momentum on its
way to development, needs more power. The place was finally
chosen as a site for the country's biggest power plant at the end
of May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
