<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Emergency Funds for Heat Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday ordered the release of 100 million dollars in emergency
federal funds to help people pay for air conditioners, fans and
other means of relief.
</P>
<P>
"In times of human crisis we have an obligation to act,"
Clinton said during an appearance in the White House briefing
room.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the money would go to people in 11 Southern and
Western states where temperature extremes have been greatest this
summer.
</P>
<P>
They are Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana,
Mississippi, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee
and Texas. In each of these 11 states, temperatures from June 1 to
July 18 were between 16 percent and 26 percent higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the summer of 1998 is on track to being the
hottest on record.
</P>
<P>
"All Americans have been deeply concerned and troubled by the
human toll of the record heat wave that has spread across many
parts of the United States," the president added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he was looking for other ways to help those most
severely affected by the heat.
</P>
<P>
He said he was ordering the Department of Health and Human
Services to release 100 million dollars from the government's
low-income home energy assistance program to the 11 hottest
states. The money can be used to buy fans and air conditioners and
to pay electric bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
