<HEADLINE> Egypt to Export Large Quantity of Crops to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will export crops worth about
7.7 million U.S. dollars to Iraq under agreements struck in line
with the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food deal, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Ministry of Agriculture has signed five contracts
with Egyptian private sector and investment companies within the
framework of the fourth phase of the oil-for-food deal starting
from July.
</P>
<P>
In addition to crops, the contracts also involve pumps, power
generators and animal feed, head of the Egyptian Trade Bureau in
Baghdad Ahmed Hosni told the Egyptian news agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The contracts are the fruit of a successful visit to Iraq on
June 16 by Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
and the talks he had with senior Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
During Gowaili's visit, the two sides signed a memo of economic
and trade cooperation with a view to boosting the volume of
bilateral trade to 250 million U.S. dollars in the coming six
months.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of Egyptian businessmen will visit Iraq early next
month for talks with Iraqi officials on the implementation of a
joint venture to manufacture irrigation and drainage pipes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Iraq have signed contracts worth 200 million dollars
over the last three phases of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal struck in 1996, Iraq is permitted to sell a
limited amount of oil every six months to buy food, medicine and
other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
