<HEADLINE> Maskhadov Accuses Moscow of Attempt to Assassinate Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 23 (Xinhua) -- President Aslan Maskhadov of
Russia's breakaway republic of Chechnya said late Thursday that
Russian secret services were behind the assassination attempt on
him early in the day.
</P>
<P>
"The attempt on my life was organized by Russian secret
services. Executors are local traitors, destructive forces," the
Itar-Tass news agency quoted him as speaking on local television.
</P>
<P>
A parked car exploded when the presidential motorcade was
driving by. Maskhadov's car caught fire but he survived because
the vehicle was armored.
</P>
<P>
So far, two of Maskhadov's bodyguards have died as a result of
the blast. Three others are still listed as in critical condition,
Tass said.
</P>
<P>
In the televised address, Maskhadov vowed to continue his cause
for an "independent Islamic Chechen state."
</P>
<P>
"I cannot die now, there is a lot of work ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Those who seek to fill the post of president should fear
popular wrath," Maskhadov said, without naming his opponents.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been running high in Chechnya, where Maskhadov
declared a state of emergency one month ago to stem rampant crime
and violence by various forces in the breakaway Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya has witnessed rising internal strife between rival
factions following the departure of Russian troops in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached earlier that year between Maskhadov
and the then national security adviser to President Boris Yeltsin,
a decision on Chechyna's status would be postponed until 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
