<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Making Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi peace talks
have made headway after three days of intense negotiations, with
the conflicting parties at Thursday's plenary session adopting a
three-point agenda for discussion.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the international mediator on Burundi Julius
Nyerere, Hashim Mbita, said that the 19 parties at the talks in
Arusha in north Tanzania on Thursday morning agreed to the agenda
of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The parties have formally accepted the agenda for discussions
on Thursday," reports reaching here quoted Mbita as saying.
</P>
<P>
The accepted agenda, aimed at giving a boost to face-to-face
talks, includes rules of a procedure for the talks, general
debate on the root cause of Burundi conflict and setting up of
sub-committees.
</P>
<P>
The talks bring the government of Pierre Buyoya, who took
power in a July 1996 coup, face to face with Hutu rebels who are
fighting the country's Tutsi-dominated army.
</P>
<P>
"We're hoping that things will move as agreed tomorrow," Mbita
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the warring parties have been consulting
each other for the past two days on starting a dialog to end
ethnic violence in the tiny central African nation which has
claimed at least 150,000 lives in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Mbita, however, admitted no thorough agreement has been
reached among the warring parties, but he hoped that the
Burundians will be of one mind to end the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, the former president of Tanzania, has asked each
party to nominate one member to help prepare Friday's plenary,
Mbita said.
</P>
<P>
The second round of the plenary session was adjourned twice on
Tuesday and Wednesday, after delegates of warring parties
disagreed on the agenda for the talks and requested Nyerere more
time for consultations among themselves.
</P>
<P>
The major point of disagreement was whether the issue of the
root cause of Burundi conflict should be discussed at the plenary
or at a sub-committee level.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has been conducting informal consultations with all
the parties and special envoys since the resumption of the second
round of talks on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has been embroiled in a civil war since 1993 when
Tutsi troops murdered the country's Hutu president, Melchoir
Ndadaye, three months after he was elected.
</P>
<P>
The international mediator on Burundi, Nyerere, last month
successfully brokered the first round of peace talks in Arusha
when all parties signed a declaration to end conflict
tentatively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
