<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. not to Rule out Military Option in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is pressing
for a diplomatic solution for the fighting in Kosovo, but could
also resort to unilateral military force or participate in a
NATO plan for action to halt the fighting.
</P>
<P>
At a House International Relations Committee hearing,
Undersecretary of Defense for Policy Walter Slocombe said: "We're
prepared to act alone if necessary. We haven't ruled it out. But
there's a distinction between whether the United States believes
it has the legal authority to act alone and whether it would in
fact in a concrete situation actually do so."
</P>
<P>
Robert Gelbard, U.S. envoy to the Balkans, said the Clinton
administration doesn't believe it needs U.N. approval for any
military action because the United Nations charter and
international law give the United States broad authority in
cases of defense.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is quite clear that we do not need a U.N.
mandate and we have made that quite clear to all our allies,"
Gelbard said.
</P>
<P>
Slocombe told the committee that NATO contingency planning
for a military intervention in the Kosovo violent conflicts was
proceeding, but there had been not decision on use of force.
</P>
<P>
Whether the United States would participate in any NATO force
in the Kosovo area was a separate decision to be made later, if
necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard said the United States was consulting with allies
about possible action in the U.N. Security Council to reinforce
its demands on Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
These demands include a pullback of Serb security forces in
the region and the start of meaningful talks with Kosovo's
Albanian leadership designed to create a political settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
