<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East African States Promote Cooperation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 23 (Xinhua) - The three nations of the
East African Cooperation (EAC) have agreed to coordinate their
foreign policies in a bid to enhance their image in the world
arena.
</P>
<P>
The permanent secretaries responsible for foreign affairs in
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda agreed early this week in a draft
memorandum of understanding that they will take concrete measures
to promote their cooperation in the foreign policy, sources said
Thursday from Arusha, northern Tanzania where the EAC Secretariat
is based.
</P>
<P>
The member states will establish liaison offices in their
foreign ministries with attention on aspects relating to foreign
affairs, making joint briefings, and soliciting support for the
EAC regional projects.
</P>
<P>
"They will provide consular services on behalf of the other
member states where they do not have embassies and consulates,
including renewal of passports and any other necessary assistance
to nationals of member states," the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
It further said that the EAC members should cooperate in
multilateral diplomacy with a view to harmonizing policies with
the Organization of African Unity (OAU), the Abuja Treaty for
African Economic Community, the Nonaligned Movement, the Group of
77 and the (British) Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also proposed collaboration among member states
in trade, investment, tourism as well as cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
In April, the three EAC member states approved a draft treaty
in a move to upgrade their cooperation into a treaty level to
help define in more clearer terms the shape and inclination of
the cooperation aimed at establishing a single market and
investment area in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded on the basis of the defunct East African
Community which collapsed in 1977 due to reasons including the
divergence of economic policies then pursued by the member
states, the continued perception of disproportionate sharing of
benefits and lack of adequate compensation mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Since its foundation, the EAC has tried to address the
shortcomings inherent in the past cooperation initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
