<HEADLINE> Philippines to Borrow From Foreign Private Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
proceed in October with its plan to borrow some 750 million U.S.
dollars to make up for the expected nearly 70 billion pesos (1.75
billion dollars) budget deficit, a senior finance official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
During a briefing for senators on the government's
legislative-economic agenda, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu
said that the government is firming up its plan to borrow from
private sources abroad some 750 million dollars either in the form
of Eurobonds or Yankee bonds.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Department of Finance will make a decision on
July 31 on who would help underwrite the bond offering. The
proceeds of the bond issuance will serve as a buffer fund for the
government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the list has been narrowed down to six from
the original eight institutions that had submitted proposals for
the bond offering.
</P>
<P>
He said a roadshow for the bond offering would be undertaken in
October in Europe and the United States. 
