<HEADLINE> U.S. Eximbank President: Time Right to Attract U.S. Capital to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- James Harmon, chairman and
president of the U.S. Export-Import Bank (Eximbank) said today
that "it is a good time to attract U.S. capital to China."
</P>
<P>
"This is the message I learned here," he told Chinese
Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao after discussions with senior Chinese
economic officials on his on-going China visit.
</P>
<P>
Now the United States' official export credit provider,
Eximbank is interested in investing in China's massive
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
His bank could also provide loans for China's small and
medium-sized enterprises via the Bank of China (BOC), China's top
foreign currency bank and Eximbank's prime partner in the country.
</P>
<P>
Eximbank may also provide technical assistance to China's
financial institutions who are now undergoing a profound
restructuring reform to cater to the market economy, a move that
may make the country's banking system "more competitive," as
Harmon put it. "This is more important than such measures as
taxation reduction," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said he appreciates China's policy of keeping its
currency stable, noting that such a decision is beneficial "for
the long-term development of China."
</P>
<P>
Established in 1934, Eximbank promotes the export of U.S. goods
by providing capital and credit guarantees for
U.S. enterprises. Its cooperation with the BOC began in 1981. The
bank is planning to set up a permanent office in China soon in a
bid to expand its China-related business.
</P>
<P>
Eximbank has joined hands with the BOC in 49 programs with a
total value of 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, either in direct
loans or export credit insurance.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also worked together to raise 2.6 billion
U.S. dollars for the import of 51 U.S.-made passenger airplanes
into China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
