<HEADLINE> Breakthrough on Kashmir Not Possible Without Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said Friday that breakthrough on the Kashmir
dispute is not possible without third party mediation.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a local news agency, the News Network
International, Ayub Khan said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his
Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee are to meet on July 29 on
the sidelines of the 10th Summit of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled meeting between the two prime ministers will be
followed by a meeting of the foreign ministers of the two
countries, said Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that no breakthrough is expected in the
scheduled meeting between Sharif and Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that for the last 50 years Pakistan
and India held several rounds of talks but the result has been
"nil" because of India's non-serious attitude.
</P>
<P>
Despite that, he said, Pakistan would continue talks with India
at every level.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), Ayub
Khan said that the recent talks in Islamabad between Pakistan and
the U.S. were satisfactory. Pakistan would continue talks on this
issue with the U.S. and other world powers.
</P>
<P>
He said that a Pakistani delegation will visit Washington next
month to hold the next round of talks.
</P>
<P>
"It is good that the Americans understand our point of view and
our position in the region," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's nuclear policy is no longer linked with that of
India, said Ayub Khan, adding that "we have our concerns...our
security concerns and in no way can we risk our security."
</P>
