<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Levels Rising at Middle, Lower Reaches of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Water levels of the middle and
lower Yangtze River have exceeded the warning line because of
continuous heavy and torrential rains over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
In Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province, torrential
rains that have been pelting down for the past three days stopped
today. The rains has turned the city into a vast expanse
of water.
</P>
<P>
Buses have now resumed service on most major streets in Wuhan,
according to local sources. However, a total of 100,000 soldiers
of the People's Liberation Army and local residents are still on
watch at the river embarkments guarding against another flood peak.
</P>
<P>
Most shops in the city shut down by the flooding also reopened
today, many still with sandbags in front of their gates.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains also hit Nanchang, capital of east China's
Jiangxi Province today, with a total rainfall of 225 mm from 8:00
am to 8:00 pm. The water level of the Jiujiang River is expected
to reach 22.3 meters within two or three days, which would be the
highest level ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
Water levels in the Xiangjiang, Zishui, Yuanjiang and Lishui
rivers in central China's Hunan Province on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze also continue to rise, due to heavy rainfalls during the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
The water level of Dongting Lake, measured at Chenglingji,
reached 34.16 meters, 2.16 meters above the warning line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
