<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Museum Entry Fee in Britain in 2001, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- British Cultural Secretary Chris
Smith announced details of 290 million pounds (478.5 million U.S.
dollars) extra funding for the arts, museums and galleries Friday,
which includes free entry to all museums and galleries next
century.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in the National Gallery in London, Smith
outlined how he would spend the extra funding for the cultural
sector over the next three years, saying 100 million pounds (165
million dollars) would be used to finance major national museums
and galleries to establish universal free entry in 2001.
</P>
<P>
"This represents a new beginning for the cultural life of this
country," Smith said. "It will give hundreds of thousands more
people the chance to enjoy the best of artistic activity, to learn
about our culture and to visit our great collections of our
nation."
</P>
<P>
Visual and performing arts get the biggest increase in funding
of 125 million pounds (206 million dollars), following a 17.5
percent cut over the last five years for which Smith himself was
partly responsible.
</P>
<P>
Smith also announced a radical overhaul of the structure of the
funding bodies that oversee the arts.
</P>
<P>
From next April a new independent watchdog will begin to
monitor efficiency and standards across the arts, and the plethora
of unelected administrative bodies, or quangos, will be
streamlined.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a radical restructuring of the landscape of
quangos we have inherited," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Elaborates Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
 Friday spelled out his administration's three-pronged foreign
policy that centers on economic diplomacy, national security and
the welfare of Filipino overseas workers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the 31st Ministerial Meeting of the
Association of Southeast Asian (ASEAN) here, Estrada said the
continuity of Philippine foreign policy pursued by his
predecessor, former president Fidel Ramos, will be the primary
thrust of his administration.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that he had retained Foreign Secretary Domingo
Siazon in his cabinet to underscore this primary goal and reaffirm
the country's various commitments before the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The function is Estrada's first exposure before an
international forum as the country's president.
</P>
<P>
In defining his administration's foreign policy, Estrada cited
five major goals which the Philippines will pursue. These are:
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening the country's bilateral security arrangements
with its major allies, which include the United States and its
close neighbors in Asia; and pushing for multilateral security
cooperation in international forums such as the United Nations and
the ASEAN Regional Forum.
</P>
<P>
-- Calling for international cooperation in dealing with the
financial turmoil gripping Asia and supporting moves to peacefully
resolve long-festering security threats, including the current
conflicts in the South China Sea, Cambodia, Korean Peninsula,
South Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
-- Establishing close links with other nations in combating
international terrorism, drug trafficking, the trafficking of
women and children, money laundering and other transnational
crimes.
</P>
<P>
-- Continuing support for a more open, freer and fairer global
trade and investment regime and reaffirming the commitment to the
goals of the ASEAN Free Trade Area, the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum, the World Trade Organization and ASEAN's ties
with the European Community.
</P>
<P>
-- Seeking global cooperation in protecting the welfare and
rights of migrant workers, especially Filipinos working and living
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada stressed that his government will strongly
support the country's joint efforts with fellow ASEAN members
Indonesia and Thailand and other countries to help Cambodia regain
political stability.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to pursue the country's commitment to assisting
in the development of Myanmar and Laos and facilitate their entry
and adjustment in the ASEAN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
