<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Telecom Network Worldclass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China has built one of "the most
modern and state-of-the-art" telecommunications networks in terms
of transmission speed, according to Gerald Butters, president of
the Optical Networking Group of Lucent Technologies Inc..
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, Butters said the Chinese
Government is obviously aware that maintaining powerful growth
momentum in the information industry is an essential element in
building an economic structure to serves sustained development
into the new century.
</P>
<P>
There are now 8.7 telephone lines for every 100 people in
China, and plans to raise the ratio to 10 to 100 by the
year 2000, and 40 to 100 by 2020.
</P>
<P>
This translates into a massive build-up of telecom
infrastructure, especially fiber optic networking over the next 22
years, Butters said.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, Lucent Technologies has been awarded
more than 300 synchronous digital hierarchy (SDH) optical
networking contracts in China, representing 650 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Butters spoke highly of the narrowing gap between China's
adoption of the latest technologies and the introduction of Lucent
Technologies' latest products in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China's networks are backed by dense
wave-length division multiplexing, the state-of-the-art technology
in fiber optic transmission. Negotiations are now underway on
technological transfer between Lucent Technologies' joint venture
in Shanghai and its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Lucent Technologies now has seven regional offices, six joint
ventures and two wholly-owned companies in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
