<HEADLINE> Togo's President Eyadema Sworn in for Second Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Gnassingbe Eyadema, who has been in a
position of power since 1967, was sworn in Friday as Togo's head
of state for the second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Togo's first election was in 1993, and the recent polling was
its second.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants at the ceremony were President Henri
Konan Bedie of Cote D'Ivoire, President Mathieu Kerekou of Benin,
and President Ibrahim Barre Mainassara of Niger.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers and deputies from the National Assembly
joined many foreign diplomats to the African country in the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Eyadema won a majority, 52.13 percent of the votes, in the June
21 presidential election, but the result was challenged by four
other opposition candidates who said it was incorrect.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional court rejected the accusation on July 2, and
declared the polling valid, clearing the way for Eyadema's
presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
