<HEADLINE> Malaysia Continues to Invest in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo said Friday that Malaysia has kept up
much-needed investment in South Africa despite its own economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nzo said ties between the two countries had strengthened over
the past few years, partly due to a substantial amount of
Malaysian investment in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the opening of a new Malaysian High
Commission in Pretoria by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, who is on a two-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Malaysian High Commission is "furthermore
an indication that Malaysia tends to maintain a strong presence
here in South Africa in the years to come," Nzo noted.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was the second largest investor in South Africa in
1996, which has pumped 1.8 billion Rand (285 million U.S. Dollars)
mainly into property development and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Telkom Malaysia and the United States-based SBC
Communications acquired a 30 percent stake in Telkom South
Africa, the largest direct investment in South Africa to date
with an inflow of 1.26 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Petronas Oil Company also acquired a 30 percent
stake in South Africa's Engen Ltd., Nzo aid.  
</P>
