<HEADLINE> Philippine President Calls for ASEAN-initiated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
 Friday pushed for the holding of an international conference on
globalization to overcome the "severe strain" caused by the
financial crisis sweeping across Asia and to speed up the recovery
of the regional economies.
</P>
<P>
Estrada made the call in his keynote address at the opening
ceremonies of the 31st Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) Ministerial Meeting here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, however, called on ASEAN to take the "intellectual
leadership" in the proposed international conference to make sure
that the outcome will truly reflect the will of the 30-year-old
organization.
</P>
<P>
"Unless ASEAN does so, others will once again shape our
destiny," the Philippine president cautioned.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said one aspect of globalization that should be given
attention to in the proposed conference is the "phenomenon of
massive amounts of capital flowing across national boundaries at
lighting speed."
</P>
<P>
"This is one of the aspects of globalization that carry an
element of risk and peril. It is an aspect of globalization that
requires the most profound examination and the most delicate
handling," he told the ASEAN foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
As the new millennium approaches, Estrada said ASEAN should
move towards greater integration to attain economic recovery that
will lead to sustained growth, greater regional peace and
stability and a more prosperous Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers from the nine ASEAN member countries are
gathering here for a two-day annual meeting which is focusing on
the financial crisis and other major economic, security and
political issues facing the region.
</P>
<P>
They will also attend the 5th ASEAN Regional Forum and the Post
Ministerial Conference to be held after the ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently groups the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore,
Malaysia, Vietnam, Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar and Brunei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
