<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Government Urged to Drop Onlooker's Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government is being
urged to stop playing the onlooker's role and to take substantive
measure to save the country's export industries from total
collapse.
</P>
<P>
If South Korea's exports plunge in the second half of this
year, the nation's credit ratings will be brought down and another
economic crisis may erupt, said the Korea International Trade
Association (KITA), in a letter to the government Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The government should immediately drop its "wait-and-see"
stance and map out additional measures as soon as possible to
raise the competitiveness of the domestic export industries, and
help resolve the liquidity crunch of smaller exporters," the KITA
said.
</P>
<P>
Although the measures announced by the government on July 10
allow small domestic exporters to receive trade financing from the
banks by just presenting approval letters of purchase issued by
large enterprises, the banks are still refusing to extend
financing, said the association.
</P>
<P>
The KITA also attributed part of the problems to the political
circle. It said the approval of the supplementary budget bill had
been delayed amid the brawl among rival political parties over the
opening of the National Assembly (parliament) session.
</P>
<P>
"It will likely take a considerable period for domestic
businesses to benefit from the expanded credit guarantee of up to
500 billion won (389 million U.S. dollars) from related agencies,
due to the delay in the National Assembly opening," the KITA said.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the association also proposed the expansion of
trade financing to larger businesses, and an increase of import
duties on foreign light industrial goods, such as textiles and
footwear, in order to protect domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
If the present bleak export situations continue, it said, the
nation will probably register a minus growth of exports this year,
for the first time since it started to sell its goods abroad in
1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
