<HEADLINE> Gore, Kiriyenko Discuss Trade, Nuclear, Space Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko met visiting U.S. Vice-President Al Gore Friday to
discuss bilateral cooperation in trade, nuclear matters and space.
</P>
<P>
After morning meetings, Russia's Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeny
Adamov said Washington had agreed to provide millions of dollars
in aid for Russia's closed nuclear towns like Sarov, the leading
Russian nuclear weapons research center.
</P>
<P>
Adamov said the United States was planning to allocate 25-30
million dollars next year for such towns.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, thousands in Sarov staged a three-hour warning
strike for back pay, fueling concern about safety at the nuclear
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The two also discussed the state of Russia's ailing economy,
hit by a financial crisis in June. Washington was a strong backer
for a 22.6 billion dollar bailout loan package for Russia.
</P>
<P>
On space cooperation issue, Russian Space Agency director
general Yuri Koptov was quoted as saying that Kiriyenko reaffirmed
Russia's pledge to continue its participation in construction of
the Alpha international space station,
</P>
<P>
The Kiriyenko-Gore meeting represents the 11th session of the
Russia-U.S. Joint Commission on Economic and Technological
Cooperation, which meets twice a year, alternately in the United
States and Russia. Kiriyenko and Gore are the co-chairmen of the
commission,
</P>
<P>
Gore, who arrived here Thursday from Ukraine, is also expected
to discuss with Russian officials the preparation for the
September visit to Russia by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Gore is scheduled to have a telephone conversation with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, who is now vacationing in Shuiskaya
Chupa, Karelia.
</P>
<P>
Gore was to leave Moscow later Friday after a joint press
conference with Kiriyenko. 
</P>
