<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan FM Says SAARC Summit to Focus on Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadirgamar said here Friday that the upcoming summit of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) would
focus on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
"The theme of this summit is the role of SAARC in a changing
world," he told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
South Asian leaders will discuss the region's "collective
responsibility towards global economic changes," he said, adding
that it was going to be an "economic summit."
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar said economic issues will be addressed at the summit
in a global context.
</P>
<P>
"So much is happening outside the region," and globalization is
taking place at a rapid pace, creating both advantages and
problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the financial crisis in Southeast Asia as one of the
problems to be addressed. The crisis is happening so close to
South Asia that "it is a natural concern for all of us."
</P>
<P>
The 10th SAARC summit is scheduled for July 29-31 in Colombo.
Senior officials from the seven member countries -- Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, Pakistan, the Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka --
began preparatory work for the summit Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries of the member states will meet Saturday
for two days of discussion, to be followed by a two-day meeting of
the SAARC foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
As SAARC delegates and foreign journalists are arriving in
Colombo, Sri Lankan authorities are tightening security in the
capital. A total of 6,000 police officers, in addition to army
soldiers, will be deployed during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar also said SAARC leaders would provide direction to
the grouping's objective of creating the South Asian Free Trade
Area (SAFTA) by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
At their summit in Male, the Maldives, in May last year, the
South Asian leaders decided to move faster from the South Asian
Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) to SAFTA, bring forward
the timetable for establishing the free trade zone from 2005 to
2001.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Eminent Persons, set up at the Male summit with
the aim of developing a long-range vision and formulating a
perspective plan of action, will deliver a report to the Colombo
summit, Kadirgamar said, adding that some decisions would be made
based on the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
