<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Encourages Fisheries Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government
encourages development of the fisheries sector, the major provider
of animal protein to the day-to-day meal of the ordinary people of
the country, the national BSS news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government will make efforts in five strategies --
extensive research, expansion, training, consulting service and
supervision in the overall fisheries sector, for implementing the
National Fisheries Policy designed to increase and develop fish
resources, alleviate poverty, raise export and preserve
environment and biodiversity, the BSS quoted officials as saying
Friday.
</P>
<P>
This has been the first fisheries policy of the country in the
past 21 years.
</P>
<P>
The government encourages the private sector in fish production
by providing training on improved technology and management,
supplying high variety of fish, fish health service and
fish-feeds, ensuring fair price and proper marketing.
</P>
<P>
The country's total domestic water bodies are 4.338 million
hectares, including 4.047 million hectares of open water bodies,
152,000 hectares of digging ponds and 138,000 hectares of coastal
shrimp farm, according to an official statement.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.492 million tons of fish were produced in the
just-ended 1997-98 fiscal year, 8.65 percent up from the
production level of the previous fiscal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
A special project, "Poverty Alleviation Through Coordinated
Fish Cultivation," during the last fiscal year helped nearly 7,000
youths employed, they said.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 5,861.8 million taka (125 million
U.S. dollars) for the fisheries sector in the country during the
fifth five-year plan period, with fish production targeted at
2.075 million tons and export targeted at 95,000 tons earning some
38,045 million taka (809.5 million dollars) in the 2001-2002
fiscal year, the last year of the five-year period, the news
agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
