<HEADLINE> DPRK Returns Remains of Three U.S. Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 24 (Xinhua)-- The remains of three U.S. soldiers,
missing in action during the 1950-53 Korean War, were returned to
the United States Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Friday handed
the remains over at the truce village of Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
The remains will be eventually handed over to the bereaved
families in the United States after going through procedures
confirming their identifications.
</P>
<P>
By Friday, the DPRK had returned the remains of 12 U.S.
servicemen killed or missing during the war.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the DPRK have been jointly searching for
the remains of U.S. soldiers since 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 U.S. servicemen were killed or went missing
during the three-year war, and about 8,100 are still unaccounted
for. 
</P>
