<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Has Strongest Economy in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Canada's biggest city Toronto has
replaced Vancouver in having the strongest economy in the country
and is expected to continue to lead Canadian cities into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board of Canada, in a new study of eight
metropolitan areas in the country, predicts strong growth this
year for all of them except Vancouver and Victoria.
</P>
<P>
With momentum building from record high levels in 1997, Toronto
is expected to lead the country this year, expanding its gross
domestic product by 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Montreal, Ottawa, Winnipeg, Calgary and Edmonton will be
nipping at their heels. Expansion of their economies is expected
to range from 3.2 percent in Winnipeg to 4.9 percent in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
But Vancouver is slowing after a decade of exuberant growth, a
victim of the Asian crisis. The city will post the weakest growth
of all at 1.8 percent this year, followed by Victoria at 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Toronto, backed by strong construction markets and surging
wholesale and retail trade, is growing almost three times as fast
as Vancouver this year, say Conference Board analysts.
</P>
<P>
They said the city's GDP should remain above four percent for
the next three years, as a result of relatively low interest rates
and good employment prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
