<HEADLINE> Festina Riders Admit Using Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a separate development a second inquiry was opened after
doping products were found in hotel rooms where members of the
Dutch TVM team were staying, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Lyon police also continued their questioning of six riders from
the banned Festina team, backed up by tests of their hair for drug
traces. Two TVM team officials were being interrogated in Pamiers,
south-western France.
</P>
<P>
Three other Festina racers were freed late on Thursday in Lille
after admitting they taken doping substances, legal sources said.
</P>
<P>
Armin Meier, a Swiss cyclist for the Festina team, was the
first to publicly confess but he declined to speak for any other
rider.
</P>
<P>
Legal sources also said police had confiscated medications
during a search of the TVM team's rooms and cars but they had to
be analysed because the labels were written in Russian.
</P>
<P>
Six Festina riders, Richard Virenque, Pascal Herve, Didier
Rous, Laurent Dufaux, Alex Zuelle and Neil Stephens were still
being heard by Lyon police on Friday as well as two Festina
officials.
</P>
<P>
The three other Festina officials in Lille -- team director
Bruno Roussel, doctor Eric Rijckaert and masseur Willy Voet --
were questioned by investigating magistrate Patrick Keil.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers at the Franco-Belgian border found 400 samples
of doping substances in Voet's car, including EPO, just before the
Tour began on July 11.
</P>
<P>
In Pamiers two TVM officials were still in detention in
connection with an earlier drugs find while three others had been
released on Thursday.  
