<HEADLINE> SAARC Committee Recommends Cooperation in Key Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A committee of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) has come up with
important recommendations regarding initiatives that member states
may take in key areas prior to the summit of the grouping later
this month.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat said Friday that at its
20th session which ended Friday in Colombo, Sri Lanka, the
Programming Committee of SAARC made important recommendations
concerning initiatives that member countries may take in such key
areas as prevention of drug trafficking and abuse, education,
culture and sports, health, population activities and child
welfare and women in development.
</P>
<P>
The report of the committee would be considered by the 25th
session of the Standing Committee of SAARC starting Saturday in
Colombo, at which the foreign secretaries of the member states are
expected to finalize preparations for the 20th session of the
Council of Ministers slated for July 27-28 and for the three-day
10th SAARC Summit starting July 29 in Colombo, the secretariat
said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The Programming Committee comprising senior officials of member
states is responsible for scrutinizing the secretariat budget,
finalizing the calendar of activities and taking up any other
matter assigned to it by the Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
It is also entrusted to consider the reports of the technical
committees and the SAARC regional centers and submit its comments
to the Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
SAARC now has 11 technical committees to formulate programs and
prepare projects in different fields, and it has four regional
centers regarding agricultural information, tuberculosis,
documentation and meteorological research.
</P>
<P>
At its meeting, the Programming Committee considered matters
relating to the activities of SAARC technical committees and SAARC
Integrated Program of Action (IPA) which covers a number of
crucial areas and activities.
</P>
<P>
It noted that commendable work has been done by the technical
committees on prevention of drug trafficking and abuse, education,
culture and sports, health, population activities and child
welfare and women in development.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote regional
cooperation in the agreed areas among its seven member countries
-- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
