<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Conservatives Demand Execution of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian hard-liners Friday staged
a demonstration in downtown Tehran, demanding the execution of
moderate Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi who was sentenced to five
years in jail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first reaction of the conservatives to the verdict
on Karbaschi, who was also banned from public office for 20 years
and fined about 180,000 U.S. dollars on charges of corruption.
</P>
<P>
Calling themselves as Hezbollah (Party of God), more than 100
protesters marched from Tehran University to the Enqelab
(Revolution) Square following the Friday prayers congregation.
</P>
<P>
Holding pictures of the Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, the demonstrators shouted: "Death to Karbaschi,
Traitor Mayor."
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was marred by a short-lived clash occurring
near the main gate of Tehran University when a pro-moderate
student holding the picture of President Mohammad Khatami tried to
block the way of the group, which was led by a van mounted with
loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
The student shouted: "Support only for Khatami."
</P>
<P>
Several hard-liners dragged him out of the way and intended to
beat him, but they were prevented by a crowd nearby.
</P>
<P>
The sentence of Karbaschi was believed to be a setback to the
moderate camp led by Khatami, who has been trying to introduce
reformist policies since taking power in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi, a well-known moderate technocrat and a close ally
of Khatami, was the highest-ranking Iranian official
charged for embezzlement since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's case has intensified the factional struggle
between the conservatives and moderates who believed the case was
politically motivated to weaken the Khatami-led government.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian public gave a mixed reaction to the verdict on
Karbaschi.
</P>
<P>
A conservative cleric from the headquarters of Friday Prayers
Congregations told Xinhua that Karbaschi was guilty of many
wrong-doings. "As a high-ranking official, Karbaschi should know
what to do and what not to do," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, a government employee shook his head while watching
the hard-line demonstration. He said that all the charges placed
by the conservatives on Karbaschi were "lies."
</P>
<P>
"He (Karbaschi) is a good man who devoted himself to the
country and the revolution," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Friday demonstration lasted for only about half an hour and
ended without violence. So far the moderate camp has been keeping
silence, in contrast to their violent reaction to the arrest of
Karbaschi in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
