<HEADLINE> Shanghai Presents HK Library With Dictionaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong library Friday
received a rare copy of Chinese Literature Dictionary, which
carries the signatures by two literary giants of China -- Ba Jin
and Bing Xin, both in their 90s.
</P>
<P>
Li Weiguo, director of the Shanghai Lexicographical Publishing
House, presented the voluminous dictionary along with 11 other
thick reference books to Tuet Sun-fan, chief librarian of Hong
Kong Regional Council Public Library here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li said at the presentation ceremony: "It is rare to have on
one book both signatures of China's two preeminent writers, and it
is particularly so considering the fact that both of them are
nearly 100 years old and have been confined to hospital for a long
period of time."
</P>
<P>
Ba Jin, born in 1904, enjoys a reputation for his novels such
as "Family", "Spring" and "Autumn", while Bing Xin, born in 1900,
is known for her children's literary works, essays and letters.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the two writers signed three copies of Chinese
Literature Dictionary, said Li, adding that one has been brought
to Hong Kong, another would be left in Shanghai and the third
would be kept in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The dictionary, which has 18,000 entries, collects the essence
of Chinese literary works throughout the past 3,000 years. The
5.5-million-word volume took more than 100 scholars 17 years to
compile.
</P>
<P>
Li mentioned another valuable book, Ci Hai, which, also
published by his publishing house, is a combination of a Chinese
dictionary and an encyclopedia. With 120,000 entries and 16
million words, Ci Hai is so far the largest comprehensive
dictionary ever published in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Li hoped that these books could be helpful to Hong Kong
readers.
</P>
<P>
Tuet, the chief librarian, said: "This is the first time that
her library received such a big donation of books from a mainland
publishing house." The Regional Council Public Library has a total
of 2.5 million books, and has planned to order 1.4 million copies
of books from the mainland in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1958, Shanghai Lexicographical Publishing House is
China's leading publisher of dictionaries and reference books. At
the on-going 98 Hong Kong Book Fair, it exhibits books worth of
400,000 HK dollars (51,000 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Secret Maps of Japanese Invaders Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archivists have discovered
370 military secret maps left by Japanese invasion troops at
Laohekou City in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The maps, drawn between 1929 and 1938, were discovered by
staff members of the Laohekou Archives as they were checking
historical records.
</P>
<P>
The maps include cities, counties and townships stretching from
Hubei Province to Jiangxi, Anhui, Hunan, Henan, Shaanxi and Sichuan
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The words "military secret" are marked on many of the maps and
the scale of most of them is 1:50,000.
</P>
<P>
Laohekou City, located in northwest Hubei Province, is a key
junction for Hubei, Henan, Sichuan and Shaanxi Provinces. It was
the Headquarters of China's No.5 War Zone.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the discovery of the maps is of great importance
for the research on the history of the Japanese invasion of China.
</P>
<P>
In March 1945, Japanese troops launched an offensive against the
city, which was defended valiantly, resulting in the killing
and wounding of 1,680 Japanese soldiers and 1,600 Chinese
casualties.
</P>
<P>
The city was seized by the Japanese in that battle, but was
later retaken by the Chinese troops in August that year.
</P>
<P>
The War of Resistance Against Japan lasted from 1937 until
1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
