<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese Ministry of Post and Telecommunications
has signed a contract with a Canadian group to conduct the
country's postal services, the Al Hayat newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said the 12-year contract stipulated that the services
include transport, collection and distribution of the mails. The
group pledged to provide a minimum investment of 50 million U.S.
dollars among the estimated total investment of 92 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni Council of Ministers approved last week
the privatization of the mobile telephone service in Yemen, the Al
Hayat daily quoted Friday the Yemeni Minister of Communications
Ahmed Al Unsi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Unsi added that the cabinet has entrusted his ministry with the
task of preparing the related documents and terms that will be
offered in a bid for international companies in a few months.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni Company for International Communications (Telyemen),
which the government owns 49 of the share, now monopolizes the
country's mobile telephone service.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian ARASCO company plans to establish a
fodder plant in Dammam at an estimated cost of 10.3 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The annual production capacity of the company would be 500,000
tonnes, the Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The company's Managing Director Abdulla Al Rabi'an said the
plant, whose construction will start in one and half months, will
begin production by mid 1999. He said that part of the plant's
machinery will be imported while the rest will be locally
manufactured at the company's factory at Al Kharj region, south of
Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the target is to develop the fodder system
in Saudi Arabia, as well as promoting its sale particularly in the
region, which there is a serious competition in the field of
agricultural crops and fodder. He indicated that the annual fodder
production in Saudi Arabia would exceed 2 million tonnes. 
</P>
