<HEADLINE> Police Authority Invites Special Supervisors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The first group of 31 special
supervisors were formally invited by the Ministry of Public
Security here today to supervise the work of the police force
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
These special supervisors, who will serve a three-year term,
are empowered to initiate supervisory measures, convey people's
complaints to related departments, and provide suggestions to the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Bai Jingfu, vice minister of Public Security, said that "in
recent years, public security bureaus nationwide have all adopted
the practice of making commitments to society and routinely
reporting to local People's Congress and People's Political
Consultative Conference, improving the image of the police force."
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the year the ministry launched a general
inspection on the law-enforcement practices of public security
bureaus nationwide, leading to the dismissal of a group of
unqualified police officers.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that unfair or illegal law-enforcement
activities such as the forced extortion of confessions, as well as
the misuse of police weapons, occur from time to time across the
country because of an imperfect supervisory system.
</P>
<P>
"Hence, the ministry has invited the special supervisors to
strengthen supervision from the outside," Bai said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister urged the police force to listen to the
supervisors' criticisms with an open mind and correct their
mistakes, and that they should not refuse to answer questions
raised by supervisors.
</P>
<P>
Among the special supervisors are Wang Yiming, vice chairman of
the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce, renowned
artists Liu Changyu and Yin Xiumei, as well as reporters from
eight Beijing-based news organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
