<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Power Cuts Occur in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- There have been more power cuts
occurring across Myanmar in recent months, resulting from
inadequate natural gas and electric power supply.
</P>
<P>
According to the Myanmar Ministry of Electric Power, hydro and
gas power plants in the country are not operating at full capacity
due to water shortage at dams and reservoirs including major water
facilities of Moebye, Inlay and Lawpyita.
</P>
<P>
Frequent failure of underground power lines, which have been in
use for about 70 years, and frequent breakdown of transformers
when overloaded also led to increased power cuts in the country,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is taking temporary measures to ensure convenience
of local subscribers, asking them to reduce power consumption as
much as they can when power is being shared and supplied in turns
to townships especially in the capital city Yangon.
</P>
<P>
According to a report on the country's financial, economic and
social conditions, the installed generating capacity (IGC) of the
state-run Myanmar Electric Power Enterprise (MEPE), the main
electricity supplier in the country accounting for 77 percent of
its total IGC, was 1,207 megawatts (mw) in 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March, compared with 1,031 mw in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The MEPE generated 4.2 billion kilowatt-hours (kwh) of
electricity in the 1997-98, 260 million kwh more than the year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Of the total generated power, 2.3 billion kwh or 55 percent was
produced by natural gas and 1.6 billion kwh or 39 percent by
hydropower.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase in power generation, electricity supply is
 still far from meeting the country's need as the economy is
developing with more involvement of the private sector and foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Electric Power, newly added in November last
year, is endeavoring to build more hydro and combined cycle power
plants in an effort to increase the country's installed generating
capacity, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, feasibility study on building more hydropower
stations  is underway by companies from Japan, the Republic of
Korea, China and some other muli-national developer groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
