<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former President's 7 Relatives Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Seven relatives of Indonesian
former president Soeharto were replaced Friday from the country's
highest legislative body, the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR), TV Indonesia reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision for the replacement was taken during a leadership
meeting of the ruling Golkar party (Functional Group) presided
over by its new chairman Akbar Tanjung on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The move was described by local press as another attempt by the
ruling political organization "to consolidate and cleanse itself
from elements of the previous regime."
</P>
<P>
Reform of the MPR will be carried out by 500 lawmakers and 500
government appointees. It will be part of an agenda for democratic
change put in place by President B.J. Habibie, who assumed the
presidential office on May 21 after the resignation of Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Habibie has appointed 41 new members of MPR on July 1 to
replace members who had retired, resigned or passed away.
</P>
<P>
The MPR's main task is to elect a president and vice president.
It is scheduled to hold an extraordinary meeting in November to
prepare new political laws for parliamentary elections in 1999.
</P>
<P>
This will be followed by the selection of a new head of state
by another meeting of the assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
