<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seized Metal In India Not Uranium: Tests Reveal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The metal seized Wednesday by
Indian Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) from a house in
Chennai, capital city of the southern State of Tamil Nadu, was not
uranium but illmenite, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The PTI said Thursday that the CBI seized 8 kilograms of
enriched uranium, which could be used in atomic energy processes,
from the house of an engineer and three people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
A scientific analysis of the samples of the metal had proved
that the it was not uranium but illmenite, the PTI said today.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Indira Gandhi Center for Atomic Energy (IGCAE)
in Tamil Nadu Placid Rodriguez, who conducted the tests, said
Friday in a statement that quantitative analysis carried out by
emission spectroscopy showed the major constituents were iron and
titanium and the x-ray examination revealed the samples to be
illmenite.
</P>
<P>
He said the samples were also analyzed by inductively coupled
plasma mass spectrometer for uranium and thorium. The
concentration of both these elements was found to be below the
detectable limit (20 ppm). 
</P>
</TEXT>
