<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Friday, ending a four-day streak of losses thanks to an afternoon
wave of buybacks by pension funds and foreign brokerages in a wide
range of issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 173.88
points, or 1.07 percent, from Thursday's close to end at 16,361.89.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 8.14 points or 0.65 percent to
1,258.01.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 400 million
shares, down from 422.75 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kawai Musical Instruments Mfg. was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo market closed minutes before the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) elected Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi as
their new president to replace outgoing party chief and Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Many traders said the outcome of the election would have only a
minor effect on the market, and investors are more interested in
seeing what steps the new prime minister and cabinet will take to
pull Japan out of recession.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered decliners 648 to 453, with 184 issues ending
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar jumped up about
1 yen when Obuchi was elected president of the LDP, but it soon
dropped on profit-taking and stayed at lower levels.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 140.53-55 yen at 5 p.m. (0800
GMT), down from 140.85-87 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from
141.30-40 yen late Thursday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
