<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Agrees to Continue Talks with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat agreed Friday to continue the
Israeli-Palestinians talks suspended after the first rounds of
negotiations earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the statement after he met with Israeli Public
Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani for one and a half hours in
the West Bank city Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference, Kahalani said the gap between the
two sides over the second stage of Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank was "very small." He said that he believed an agreement
would be signed very soon.
</P>
<P>
No concrete date and place for the further talks were announced.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Kahalani meeting came amid doubts about in what
direction the newly-resumed Israeli-Palestinian talks will go --
to a total collapse or to be continued.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have kept the Israelis in the dark for two
days as to whether they agree to resume the talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks broke down abruptly Wednesday after two rounds of
discussions resulted in no progress. The PNA complained that the
Israelis had not brought any new proposals to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
At issue was the American proposal calling for a 13.1 percent
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank. The Palestinians have
accepted the proposal, but Israeli rejected it on security
grounds.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian Negotiator Saeb Erekat was quoted by Israeli
TV as saying that although the Palestinians agreed to resume
talks with the Israelis, they would not intend to negotiate, but
just to listen to the Israeli views on the U.S. initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made it clear that the U.S. plan was
nonnegotiable, and the only way to push forward the peace process
is for Israel to announce its acceptance of the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
