<HEADLINE> Japanese LDP's New Chief pledges to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) President Keizo Obuchi pledged Friday to revitalize
the country's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
"The pressing issue facing us is to reconstruct the Japanese
economy and get rid of the people's uncertainty," Obuchi, 61, who
is expected to become prime minister late this month, told a press
conference shortly after being elected president of the LDP.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese economy bears responsibility for Asia and the
whole world. We hope to convert the minus growth into plus
growth," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also vowed to cut income tax on high-income Japanese
people whose annual income is above 30 million yen (about 210,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives (lower house) is expected to make
Obuchi prime minister on July 30 to replace Ryutaro Hashimoto, who
resigned after the LDP's defeat in the July 12 House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that he would form a powerful party leadership and
cabinet by putting the right people in the right posts.
</P>
<P>
He also said he would appoint a "competent and reliable" person
as finance minister.
</P>
<P>
He said his government hopes that the Diet (parliament) will
pass legislation "as soon as possible" to implement the "bridge
bank" plan to clean up bad debts of the country's failed financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"The bridge bank scheme is the key to revitalizing the nation's
ailing economy," Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of bridge banks to take over failed financial
institutions is the centerpiece of the government's plans, which,
released on July 2, are aimed at salvaging Japan's financial
system from the bad-loan mess. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
