<HEADLINE> EU Approves First European SMEs Joint Venture Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Friday
approved the first two projects of the Joint European Venture
program for small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
One project is an Italian-British project known as Ecotecna to
improve road safety by developing a virtual reality driving
simulator for scooters.
</P>
<P>
The other is Spilker GmbH between France and Germany focusing
on making dies and cylinders for the production of self-adhesive
labels, cardboard and plastic.
</P>
<P>
The Joint European Venture program is designed to support and
encourage new transnational joint ventures between small and
medium-sized enterprises in the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
The program, initiated by European Enterprise Policy
Commissioner Christos Papoutsis and Economic and Financial Affairs
Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy, has a budget of 80-100
million ECU (88-110 million U.S. dollars) for the period from 1998
to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The budget, expected to finance 1,500 joint ventures among
SMEs, funds up to 50 percent of the cost for setting up a joint
venture between at least two SMEs from different EU member states
with an overall maximum contribution of 100,000 ECU (110,000
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Once the joint venture is operational, the Joint European
Venture program may contribute up to 10 percent of the total
investment made toward the enterprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Improve Competitiveness of Recycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission proposed
on Friday to improve the competitiveness of industries using
recyclable energies and materials in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
European Industry Commissioner Martin Bangemann and Environment
Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard jointly made the initiative by
pointing out the major problems facing the recycling industries.
</P>
<P>
Key problematic areas were found in the increasing cost for
waste treatment, the lack of interest by some industries in
recycling materials and the lack of market transparency that leads
to low investment.
</P>
<P>
The commissioners proposed harmonizing the test methods and
specifications, analyzing product standards, exploring the
possibility of replacing those dangerous materials and studying
the feasibility of the marking system.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission attaches importance to recycling and
environment in its fifth Research and Development Program that
covers the period from 1999 to 2002 after earlier efforts
materialized in improved recycling in industries.
</P>
<P>
The biggest increase of use of recyclable energies and
materials was recorded by the non-ferrous metal industry with 57
percent, followed by the paper industry at 46 percent, the glass
industry at 45 percent and the ferrous metal industry at 43
percent.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry, according to figures published by the
commission, posted significant progress in 1997 when its recycling
rate rose to around 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Recover on Stronger Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares recovered from
a morning sell-off to close only marginally lower, thanks mainly
to stronger performance by Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended only 3.2 points lower at
2,745.5, well above its opening low of 2,705.3 points which was
struck in early trade following the two percent fall on the Dow
Jones Industrial Average overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell nearly 196 points to
about 8,933.
</P>
<P>
But both Japan's Nikkei and Hong Kong's Hang Seng defied the
fall in the Dow, and the election of the reportedly market
unfriendly Keizo Obuchi to lead Japan's Liberal Democratic Party,
to close higher.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei closed 174.0 points higher at 16,362.0 and the Hang
Seng climbed off opening lows to an 81.2 point gain to 8,257.4.
</P>
<P>
"The reaction in Japan is promising as it means their local
market seems happy with the likely selection (by Japan's Liberal
Democratic Party) of Obuchi as leader," a Lodge and Partners
broker said.
</P>
<P>
He said the local market had been "saved by the resilience in
Asia today but we are still expecting a further softening on Wall
Street tonight".
</P>
<P>
Overall, 283.8 million shares changed hands worth 961.2 million
Australian dollars (595.94 million U.S. dollars). Falling stocks
outnumbered rising stocks by 617 to 426.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index softened 5.9 to 1,065.1 points and all
industrials index eased 0.8 to 4,826.6 points.
</P>
<P>
The better performers among the leaders included Telstra,
Foster's, National Australia Bank and retail stocks.
</P>
<P>
Telstra surged 10 cents as the market searched for defensive
stocks. Foster's Brewing added five cents after announcing
Thursday its acquisition of Brierley's Austotel chain for 186
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
All of the major banks were firmer apart from ANZ which dropped
44 cents or 3.9 percent, National Australia Bank ended 34 cents
firmer,  Commonwealth climbed 17 cents and Westpac climbed 3.1
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended steady with a 1.7 point rise to 1,100.5
after gold bullion recovered 80 U.S. cents to 293.60 U.S. dollars
in Sydney trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
