<HEADLINE> ASEAN Wishes to See Free, Fair Elections in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) said here Friday
that they wish the forthcoming elections in Cambodia will be
"free, fair, credible and peaceful."
</P>
<P>
The ministers, in their respective statements at the 31st ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting (AMM), also welcomed Cambodia to join the
regional political, economic and security group, hopefully at the
end of this year or next year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Nguyen
Manh Cam said that as Cambodia's close neighbor, Vietnam has
followed with keen interest in the developments in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam sincerely hopes that the elections will be successful
and Cambodia would enjoy peace and stability to develop itself and
would soon be admitted to the great ASEAN family," Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is also Vietnam's hope that the Sixth ASEAN
Summit to be held at the end of this year in Hanoi, Vietnam, will
translate the ideal of an ASEAN-10 into reality with the admission
of Cambodia as a member.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said his
country wishes to commend all parties in Cambodia, the ASEAN
Troika including Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines and other
parties concerned for their efforts in making the elections
possible.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the successful outcome of a free and
fair election in Cambodia will facilitate the restoration of peace
and political stability in the country, and see Cambodia joining
ASEAN as the 10th member. With all Southeast Asian countries in
together in ASEAN, the vision of ASEAN-10 would be realized and
the whole of Southeast Asia would be marching in tandem into the
next millennium," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said ASEAN, through
the Troika, has helped the Cambodian to put in place a process
that "we all hope will lead to free, fair and credible elections
in Cambodia."
</P>
<P>
"Cambodia will then rightfully take its place as our tenth
member so that ASEAN will embrace all of Southeast Asia as one
single family of nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said Indonesia is
watching very closely the political process in Cambodia that will
culminate in the general elections on July 26.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential for the credibility of this process that all
parties have equal access to media and that it is free, fair and
peaceful so that it will lead to the creation of a stable
government that can ensure lasting peace and stability for the
Cambodian people," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Indonesia hopes to welcome Cambodia as a member
of ASEAN this year, saying "this would fulfill our shared vision
of an ASEAN comprising all 10 Southeast Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, the chairman of
the 31st AMM, said ASEAN encourages the Cambodian brothers to take
hold of their future by uniting for a free, fair and credible
election, adding that "their success in that endeavor is success
for ASEAN too."
</P>
<P>
During the 31st AMM, Chem Widhya, Cambodia's permanent
secretary of the Foreign Ministry, introduced Cambodia's
preparations for the elections and the commitment to join ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
"Though not perfect, our preparations hereto have been credited
by a large and critical international audience as being fair," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also thanked all ASEAN member countries for
sending observers to Cambodia for the general elections.
</P>
<P>
This decision and the generous support given by numerous donor
countries to physically enable these elections to take place
constitute a great encouragement for the Cambodian people, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"They are perceived as a vote of confidence in the capability
of the Cambodian authorities to hold their first national
elections organized on their own since the signature of the Paris
Peace Agreement in 1991," he said.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar joined ASEAN last year which then included
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam. ASEAN decided to delay Cambodia's admission due to
the newly-emerged political turmoil inside the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
