<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Holds Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar held its
ground Friday unfazed by confirmation that Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi had been elected the new leader of Japan's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Despite some initial weakness in both the Japanese yen and the
domestic currency immediately following the announcement, traders
said Obuchi's election had been largely factored in.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the local session at 61.92 U.S.
cents, from 61.93 here previously.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets had been poised for the news from Japan for
some days, but ANZ Investment Bank head of securities trading
Jeremy Colless said the actual event had provided no surprises.
</P>
<P>
"He was the favorite to win it even if he wasn't the favorite
of markets. Therefore his win has been pretty well priced in,"
Colless said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Japanese announcement, the currency had spent the
session range-trading in a 61.95 to 62.30 U.S. cent band as it
tracked the yen.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of Obuchi's success pushed the U.S. dollar
back over 141.00 yen from around 140.50.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the Australian dollar wobbled around 62 U.S. cents,
dipping to 61.95 and rebounding to 62.20 before settling just
below 62.
</P>
<P>
In the foreign exchange market, the Australian dollar closed at
87.47 yen, from 87.75, and at 1.1056 German marks, from 1.1081.
</P>
</TEXT>
