<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Singapore Bank Becomes Larger Through Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Development Bank of
Singapore (DBS), the largest in the country, has acquired the Post
Office Saving Bank (POSBank), the fifth largest in the country, in
a bid to further strengthen its position as the largest Southeast
Asian bank and one of the largest banks in Asia.
</P>
<P>
S. Dhanabalan, Chairman of the DBS, told a press conference
Friday afternoon that the Government of Singapore has accepted the
proposal for the acquisition that combines the largest and the
fifth largest Singapore financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
POSBank's existing business undertakings, including all its
branches and its ATM network, and Credit POSB, will be transferred
as going concerns to DBS and staff of POSBank and its subsidiaries
will cross over to become DBS staff on existing terms of
employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
But the POSBank Tower (under construction) and some equity/bond
investments will be returned to the government, he added.
</P>
<P>
DBS is already Southeast Asia's largest and the 90th largest
bank in the World. The POSBank has been a leader in providing
retail banking services to the Singaporean public in its 26-year
history as a statutory board.
</P>
<P>
After the merger, the DBS and its subsidiaries will have assets
of approximately 93.4 billion Singapore dollars (about 54.94
billion U.S. dollars), customer deposits of approximately 59.3
billion Singapore dollars (about 34.88 billion U.S. dollars), and
shareholders' funds of approximately 9.4 billion Singapore dollars
(about 5.53 billion U.S. dollars), based on the position as at 31
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Following the privatization, the POSBank will operate as a
division within the DBS and continue to service its depositors and
customers without changing its brand.
</P>
<P>
Currently, interest earned on POSBank savings deposits is tax
exempt, the tax exemption will have to be withdrawn as POSBank
will now be part of a commercial entity.
</P>
<P>
S. Dhanabalan said the acquisition provides a number of key
advantages including:
</P>
<P>
-- to strengthen the position of the largest retail banking
business in Singapore;
</P>
<P>
-- to extend domestic market coverage;
</P>
<P>
-- to increase its distribution to over 170 branches and more
than 950 ATMs nationwide;
</P>
<P>
-- to enlarge and diversify its deposit base;
</P>
<P>
-- and to increase economies of scale with greater operational
efficiencies through the integration and rationalization of the
DBS Bank's business.
</P>
<P>
"We view this acquisition as a unique opportunity to strengthen
DBS Bank's market leadership in Singapore, particularly in retail
banking," Dhanabalan said. "The POSBank retail network and brand
are very well known and effective in mobilizing savings, and for
this reason we intend to retain and build on POSBank's established
identity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The merger is in line with Singapore government's policy to
encourage local banks to merge with each other so as to
consolidate the industry and create fewer, but larger and stronger
banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
