<HEADLINE> S. Leone Begins Trial of Coup Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A military court in Sierra Leone
Thursday began the trial of about 38 members of the military
junta led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who seized power from
elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in a coup in May last year.
</P>
<P>
A report from Freetown said the 38 persons were charged with
mutiny, failure to suppress mutiny and treason, according to the
laws applicable in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Put on trial Thursday is Brigadier General Sesay Koroma,
brother of Major Koroma and the Chief of Defense Staff in his
cabinet known as the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council.
</P>
<P>
Others were former Director of Defense Information, Colonel
Abdul Sesay, Corporal Tamba Gborie who announced the coup on
radio, and a colonel Abu Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
Koroma and his followers were driven out of Freetown in
February this year by the west African peace-keeping force known
as ECOMOG. He has been on the run since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
