<HEADLINE> Hunan Witnessed Record Flood Water Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Flood water levels in some areas
in central China's Hunan Province have hit record highs over the
past few days resulting from torrential rainfall which has
exacerbated the already serious flood situation.
</P>
<P>
The Lishui River Valley Hydrological Station recorded flood
waters levels of 62.25 meters at 18:30 (Beijing time) on
Thursday. The level beat the previous record by 0.65 meters and
was 4.65 meters above the danger mark. The station also recorded a
flow rate of 19,000 cu.m./second, or 1,400 cu.m./second more than
previous high.
</P>
<P>
Other stations also reported record water levels which in many
cases exceeded the danger mark. The water level in Dongting Lake
continues to rise, according to the provincial flood control
headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
