<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stopping The Smuggling Of Relics From China's Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in Chongqing
have recovered 164 rare relics that came from the Three Gorges
area during a campaign to stop smuggling through the post office.
</P>
<P>
According to one customs officer, the items were discovered in
16 cases of mail smuggling cases. Some are highly protected items.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam is the world biggest water conservation
project and covers large parts of southwestern and central
China. The reservoir will mean inundating many areas along the
Yangtze River, so a search for relics was started.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale excavation work has also led to the discovery
of a large number of relics.
</P>
<P>
And, of course some people have managed to gain possession of
the relics and have tried to smuggle them out of China using
assumed names.
</P>
<P>
So, Customs officers in Chongqing, China's largest city which
is in the southwestern part of the country have tightened their
checks on the mail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
