<HEADLINE> Yield of Early Rice to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- This year's early rice yield is
expected to drop due to the decrease of planted areas and recent
floods, according to an official from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"However, the drop will be marginal," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that this year's grain harvest will be affected
to a "limited" extent due to the fact that early rice accounts for
only a tenth of the annual grain output.
</P>
<P>
China harvested 45.78 billion kg of early rice in 1998, with
statistics showing that planted areas for related crops fell
by 4.4 percent on 1997 levels. Floods in the major rice producing
areas, including Jiangxi, Hunan and Hubei provinces, have also had
an adverse affect on maturing rice during the July period.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that harvesting has concluded in related
areas and farmers are currently threshing and drying the crops.
</P>
<P>
He note that autumn grain, which contributes 70 percent of the
country's annual grain output, is thriving. He predicted
that the country will fulfill this year's output target of
492.5 billion kg of grain. He added that autumn grain was planted
on additional 22,000 ha during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau projects that the yield of this
year's summer grain will hit 113.1 billion kg, down 11 percent
over last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke072439 -"Flexible Engagement" Causes Controversy Inside ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Most foreign ministers attending
the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) expressed here Friday
their strong opposition to the proposed change in ASEAN's policy
from "non-interference" to "flexible engagement."
</P>
<P>
"Flexible engagement," raised by Thailand and supported by the
Philippines, means that when domestic developments in a country
have transboundary effects, other member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) can give advice to
or press the country to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We need stronger engagement among ASEAN and we also need
equally to adapt ourselves to changing times. We must be flexible
in our approach to the tasks at hand while steadfastly adhering to
the long-standing principles for which ASEAN has stood and which
have truly served us well," Thailand Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan reiterated his stance on the "flexible engagement" at the
AMM.
</P>
<P>
However, most ASEAN members are "strongly opposed" to the idea.
</P>
<P>
The principle of non-intervention in each other's internal
affairs has served ASEAN well and should therefore not be
abandoned at this time when ASEAN stood at a cross roads of its
history, Singapore Foreign Minister Shunmugan Jayakumar said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Besides non-interference, other basic principles that shaped
ASEAN's success include sovereign equality and decisions by
consultation and consensus; avoidance of the use of force to
change established governments or an internationally recognized
political order; open economies; and making ASEAN the cornerstone
of each country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
These principles have been tried and proven sound and have
given the direction in which ASEAN should evolve, Jayakumar said,
adding that this is why the "ASEAN Way" was really driven by
process and not by outcome.
</P>
<P>
"They (these principles) have contributed to ASEAN's success in
the past, and will continue to do so in the future. Discarding
them will not make ASEAN stronger. To the contrary, to do so may
imperil ASEAN's future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Non-intervention, however, does not mean indifference to each
other's well-being, Jayakumar added.
</P>
<P>
"The growing web of functional, social, financial and economic
ties that link ASEAN members already impels us to work together,
advise each other and coordinate national policies in many areas.
We can do more of this without abandoning basic principle," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 31st AMM, Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi said that non-intervention is the internationally
accepted principle governing relations between states and is
contained in all ASEAN agreements. The principle has served to
maintain the unity within the ASEAN diversity.
</P>
<P>
"To abandon this time-tested principle would set us on the path
towards eventual disintegration," he said.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said that the stable political environment and the
positive inter-state relations between ASEAN member countries have
much to the adherence to the principle of non-interference.
</P>
<P>
Under the non-intervention policy, the ASEAN countries have not
only commented and criticized, but also expressed reservations
when necessary, but "we do all this quietly," Badawi said, adding
that "criticizing loudly, posturing adversarially and
grandstanding bring less results and does more harm than good."
</P>
<P>
"I see little benefit in discussing this divisive issue of
interfering in each other's international affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Nguyen
Manh Cam also expressed the similar opinion.
</P>
<P>
He said in his statement that in the context of the present
challenges, strengthening ASEAN's time-tested unity and
cooperation has become ever more essential.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's unity has been built upon the basic principles
including non-interference into the internal affairs of one
another and the settlement of differences and disputes by peaceful
means, Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that these principles have helped ASEAN alive and
thriving and contributed to enhancing relationship with outside
partners, especially dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
The other ASEAN members -- Brunei, Laos, Indonesia and Myanmar
-- also voiced their opposition to "flexible engagement" before
the ministerial meeting which opened Friday and will close on
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Protesters Demand Harsher Punishment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian conservatives held a
protest here Friday, demanding harsher punishment of the moderate
major Gholamhossein Karbaschi, who was sentenced to five years in
jail for corruption Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi was also banned from holding public office for 20
years, fined 1.6 million rials (530,000 U.S. dollars) and
sentenced to 60 lashes by a Tehran court.
</P>
<P>
But he will remain free on bail until he decides whether he
will appeal or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
