<HEADLINE> Ugandan Police Arrest Over 40 Car Thieves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police arrested over 40
businessmen and impounded suspected stolen vehicle spare parts at
Kisekka market here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The raid, conducted by a contingent of 300 policemen, was
followed by operations by Uganda Revenue Authority (URA) and
Uganda Electricity board officers who sealed off and disconnected
power from some shops, the New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some of the businessmen were caught as they had just opened
their shops for business.
</P>
<P>
"The policemen took engines, side mirrors, head-lamps, fitting
equipment, spare doors, wheel cups and wind screens among
others," a market committee member was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said even shops of popular companies like BMK,
Daido, Masaku and Muko which have import licenses, were also
affected by the operation.
</P>
<P>
The police said there are some commodities like fuel which
they did not impound.
</P>
<P>
A URA official said the Kisekka market is known for stolen
motor vehicle parts and traders there are notorious for
non-payment of taxes. 
</P>
