<HEADLINE> 2 More Parties Emerge in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Two more political parties emerged
in Nigeria Thursday, as the country is on its way to a new
transition to civil rule process.
</P>
<P>
The People's Democratic Movement (PDM) launched in Lagos is
actually a come-back of the party with the same name formed by
late Major-General Musa Yar'adua, which was denied registration
under the transition program of late military leader General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The party now has Alhaji Lawal Kaita as its national chairman
and Dubem Onyia as national secretary.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued in Lagos Wednesday after a meeting
aimed at perfecting its strategy under the new dispensation, the
party pledged to cooperate with the government of General
Abdulsalam Abubakar for the success of the transition program.
</P>
<P>
In Port Harcourt, a party known as the New Rivers Forum (TNRF)
was floated by Chief Ebenezer Isokrari, former secretary to the
Rivers State Government and chieftain of the dissolved United
Nigeria Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
Isokrari, announcing the birth of the party at a press
conference and describing himself as the facilitator, said all
the positions in the party were vacant so as to allow credible
persons to vie freely and fairly.
</P>
<P>
The first party formed under Abubakar's new transition program
was the Democratic Advance Movement floated Tuesday in Lagos by
Tunji Braithwaite, a Lagos-based lawyer and politician.
</P>
<P>
Braithwaite was the presidential aspirant of the just
disbanded Gross-roots Democratic Movement (GDM), but the GDM later
chose to have Abacha as its candidate, together with the four
other parties registered by Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The emerge of the three parties followed the announcement of
the new transition program by Abubakar last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar ordered the dissolution of all the political parties
to pave the way for the registration of new parties. He pledged
to hand over power to an elected civilian president on May 29,
1999 after free and fair elections monitered by international
observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
