<HEADLINE> German Firm to Start Study on W. African Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A German firm known as P.L.E. will
soon conduct a full feasibility study on the proposed West
African Gas Pipelines project that will send Nigeria's rich
natural gas resources to its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
A report carried by the Daily Times said Friday that five oil
companies from Nigeria, Ghana and the Republic of Benin will sign
a contract next week with the German firm for the feasibility
study.
</P>
<P>
The report identified the five firms as Shell, Nigerian Gas
Company, Chevron, Ghana National Petroleum Corporation and an
unnamed firm from the Benin Republic.
</P>
<P>
The study will focus on the potential of the gas market in
Ghana, Togo and Benin, the pipeline system, production volume,
project cost and the suitable price for the gas, the report said,
adding that the study will be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The West African Gas Pipeline project was proposed four years
ago with a total cost of 260 million U.S. Dollars, but it has
been stalled due to fund constraint and disagreement over gas
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
