<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urged to Intervene in Angola Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime
Gama has revealed that his government has sent a letter to U.N.
Chief Kofi Annan asking him to intervene in Angolan peace process
so as to avoid the breakout of a new war in the country.
</P>
<P>
Gama revealed Thursday in Sal island, Cape Verde where he is
attending a contact team meeting of the Community of
Portuguese-speaking countries on mediation in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Angola is very urgent and the danger of war
in eminent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The appeal by the Portugal government was made at a time when
Annan has not appointed any new U.S. special envoy to Angola
since the death of Blondin Beye in an air crash in Cote d'Ivoire
at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Lisbon believed that if a new envoy is named to fill in the
sad vacancy emptied by the death of Beye, the peace process in
Angola will be speeded up, said Gama.
</P>
<P>
The political and military situation in Angola is degenerating
in the past few weeks, giving rise to a great possibility for a
large scale armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
The former rebel movement the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) still refused to comply with the
resolution of the U.N. Security Council, thus wearing out the
patience on the part of the Angolan government. And the peace
process in Angola is facing a difficulty more than any other
time.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister suggested that U.N. secretary-general
Annan visit Angola again and get in touch with the signatories of
the 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord which ended the 19-year old civil
war and restore dialog between the Angolan government and UNITA.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that copies of the letter to Annan was also sent
to the United States, Russia and Portugal, the three observer
countries of the Angola peace process as well as to the Angolan
government and UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
