<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Restores Air Link with UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Direct air link between Nigeria and
Britain will resume soon after 14 months' break following an
order to this effect Thursday by the Nigerian Head of State,
General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's order with immediate effect was contained in a
statement in Abuja signed by Alhaji Gidado Idris, the Secretary
to the Government of the Federation.
</P>
<P>
Air link between Nigeria and Britain was severed in May last
year, when Britain banned all Nigeria-registered aircraft from
flying into its airspace for their alleged poor safety standards.
Nigeria retaliated immediately by banning all Britain-registered
aircraft from flying into its airspace.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that over 19 billion Naira (about 224 million
U.S. Dollars) was lost in revenue to both sides in the aviation
row. The British Airways, which operated 10 flights to Nigeria a
week, with higher passenger patronage, bigger aircraft and higher
fares, lost even more than its Nigerian counterpart, the Nigerian
Airways.
</P>
<P>
When negotiations between the two sides for the resumption of
air links had failed, the British side reportedly lifted the ban
unilaterally, but the Nigerian government denied its knowledge of
this.
</P>
<P>
The sight of a breakthrough in the row came last Monday, when
Abubakar addressed the nation on his administration's major
policies and expressed the wish to restore air link with Britain,
the U.S. and other nations.
</P>
<P>
According to a media report, British Airways Africa Regional
Manager Andy Stern has said the company will resume operation
next Wednesday with a new Boeing 777 aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
