<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obuchi Elected President of Japan's LDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi was elected president of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) Friday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is expected to be designated prime minister by the House
of Representatives (lower house) on July 30 to replace outgoing
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who resigned on July 13
after the LDP's devastating loss in the July 12 House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
"I'm deeply and keenly aware of my responsibilities at this
time of severity. I will do my best for the sake of the party and
the nation to overcome the difficult situation," Obuchi told his
party colleagues shortly after he was elected.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, polled a majority on the first secret ballot at a
meeting of LDP members of both houses of the Diet (parliament) and
representatives from 47 prefectures.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is expected to start soon selecting the top three LDP
executives -- secretary general, chairman of the Policy Research
Council and chairman of the Executive Council, LDP sources said.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to begin the process of forming a new
cabinet, they added.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi will serve out the rest of Hashimoto's term until the
end of September next year.
</P>
<P>
The other two candidates in the race were former Chief Cabinet
Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama, 72, and Health and Welfare Minister
Junichiro Koizumi, 56.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi won 225 of of 411 valid votes cast, with Kajiyama
winning 102 and Koizumi 84. There was one valid vote.
</P>
<P>
A total of 414 LDP members, including 367 LDP Diet members and
47 prefectural representatives of the party's local branches, were
eligible to vote in the race for the LDP's presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
