<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Improvement In Northern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The economy in north China's port
city of Tianjin has begun to pick up with increased fixed assets
spending and restructured exports to counter the downturn caused
by the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, local GDP was up 8.79
percent to 60.9 billion yuan, from the same 1997 period, and fixed
assets investment this year is expected to be 15 percent more than
last year, at 42.7 billion yuan, with focus on infrastructure,
housing, technology improvement, and hi-tech development.
</P>
<P>
During the January-June period, the city spent 7.8 billion yuan
on basic construction, 3.1 billion yuan on real estate, and nearly
3.9 billion yuan on technology.
</P>
<P>
The city increased exports to the U.S., Europe, Africa, and the
Commonwealth of Independent States to offset losses caused by the
financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the U.S. went up nearly 44 percent during the first
half of this year, from the same 1997 period, and those to France
up 9 percent and to Italy, 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city had 4.68 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign trade
during the first half of the year, up 14.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 percent of exports were machinery and electronics
products.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has checked the fall in overseas investment and added
470 overseas-funded enterprises during the first half of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Tourist Spot Promoting Tourism To Offset Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Guilin, the popular Chinese tourist
destination is increasing its tourism promotion to offset the
effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although President Clinton's visit to the city in early July
was good news, the number of overseas tourists fell 19.5 percent,
and income from tourism was down 20.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tourism officials say the decline is mainly the result of
24.9 percent fewer Japanese tourists and 80 percent fewer South
Koreans in the first six months. But, they're not too pessimistic
about the future because they believe that business can get over
the slump in the second half with a little effort.
</P>
<P>
Kang Tianbao, Guilin's Vice-mayor in charge of tourism, says
that the city will focus on two countries -- the United States and
Japan -- and on two regions -- Hong Kong and Taiwan. In the past
few months, the city sent four delegations to Japan to promote
tourism.
</P>
<P>
After Clinton's visit, the city drafted a plan to promote the
route followed by Clinton with the cities involved: Xi'an,
Beijing, Shanghai, and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, television stations in Hong Kong began showing a
documentary on Guilin's tourist activities and recently, the city
invited many Taiwanese media members to visit the city.
</P>
<P>
One good sign is the luxury hotels that have been full since
mid-July, one city official says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000 Australian Students Rally Against Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- About 4,000 Australian
high-school students in Australia's major capital cities of
Sydney, Melbourne, Canberra and Adelaide took to streets Friday in
protest against Pauline Hanson's racism.
</P>
<P>
Waving anti-racism placards and chanting slogans, the students
marched in a nationwide campaign against racism advocated by
Australian federal MP Pauline Hanson.
</P>
<P>
"Migrants are welcome, racists are not" and "Hey hey ho ho
Pauline Hanson has to go," the students in Sydney and Canberra
chanted during the afternoon rallies.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, the biggest industrial and business center in
Australia, an anti-racism rally by up to 2,000 school students
outside Australian Prime Minister John Howard's Sydney office
passed off peacefully Friday.
</P>
<P>
The students chanted slogans outside Howard's office for about
15 minutes before moving on to make speeches at Circular Quay near
the Opera House, Australia's most famous tourism attraction.
</P>
<P>
About 30 police were on hand outside Howard's office and
barricades had been erected in case of trouble, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
In Melbourne, the nation's second biggest industrial and
business center, local police estimated 1,200 high-school students
descended on central Melbourne for an anti-racism rally Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Australia's capital city of Canberra Friday afternoon, about
300 students rallied in the city's downtown area and marched along
the city's major avenue Northbourne for about one hour.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 students in Adelaide, capital of South Australia
state, rallied against the racist policy of Pauline Hanson in the
city center Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sean Healy, a national walk-out rally coordinator in Sydney,
said in a telephone interview with Xinhua that similar activity
will be held several days later in Brisbane, the third largest
city in Australia, because of school holidays.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Australian government Friday
rejected calls by former prime minister Malcolm Fraser for the
ruling Australian Liberal and National parties to form a
government with the opposition the Labor Party in order to lessen
One Nation's influence in politics.
</P>
<P>
Fraser Thursday predicted the next federal election would
result in a hung parliament, leaving One Nation to wield massive
influence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
