<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 07:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Elect New President in October: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's incumbent President Elias
Hrawi has ruled out seeking another term, indicating the
country will hold a presidential election this fall, the Daily
Star newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"President (Carlos) Menem invited me to visit Argentina but I
sent him my apologies because my mandate would have expired by the
time of the visit," Hrawi was quoted as telling a delegation of
members of the Lebanese diaspora in Argentina on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper interpreted Hrawi's remarks as a hint that the
president really wanted to quit the presidency so a new
presidential election is inevitable in October when Hrawi's term
expires.
</P>
<P>
Before this, some lawmakers who had met Hrawi also said that
the president really wanted to have a rest.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi, 72, a Maronite Christian, was elected president in
1989 with Syria's strong backing.
</P>
<P>
When his first term expired in 1996, parliament voted to pass
an one-time constitutional amendment that year, allowing him to
stay on for an extra three-year-and-half term.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats have noted that as his term nearing its end,
all signs pointed to the predication that he would not seek
a third term.
</P>
<P>
Under Lebanon's constitution, the country's top political posts
are equally shared between Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister always comes from Sunni Muslims, the
parliamentary Speaker from Shiite Muslims and the president from
Maronite Christians.
</P>
<P>
Until now, there is no clear contender for the
presidency. Western diplomats said Syria will has the last say in
choosing the new head of state.
</P>
<P>
Syria, with 40,000 troops stationed in Lebanon as
peacekeepers, is a main power broker in the country, which
is recovering from the 15-year-old civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
