<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wants To Add Two World Heritage Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China is cleaning up its most
famous imperial park and sacrificial altar to apply for "World
Heritage" status for them.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO will approve the new group of cultural sites for the
list in December and the Chinese government chose the Summer
Palace and the Temple of Heaven as its applicants this year.
</P>
<P>
It has put nearly 10 million yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars)
into repair work for the Temple of Heaven, according to Lou
Lianju, of the temple administration office. They've torn down all
snack bars around the Hall of Prayer for Good Harvests and moved
souvenir shops. They also planted trees throughout the garden
around the temple and the other cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
A new hall will show the ancient praying ceremony to visitors,
Lou said, and the management decided to remove the iron guards on
the Echo Wall's stone steps. The curved wall, which has thousands
of visitors daily, repeats the sound of people's voices.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of the Summer Palace in suburban Beijing
have also tried to restore its ancient appearance and workers have
moved snack stalls and power line poles away from central scenic
spots.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO says that the original forms of cultural relics must be
preserved and has special funds for preserving those sites, which
are not to be attacked even in time of war.
</P>
<P>
There are now 552 cultural and natural heritage sites. China's
present sites are the Forbidden City, the Great Wall, the
Zhoukoudian Peking Man Ruins, the Potala Palace in Lhasa, and 15
others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Water-Efficiency Project For Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province will build a water saving project using a sprinkler
system on 333,300 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 3.6 billion yuan and be completed in five
years, Provincial Governor Zhang Guoguang says.
</P>
<P>
It will expand the irrigated area in 10 cities and 36 counties
from 30 percent to 44 percent. When completed, the project will
add 1.8 billion kg of grain annually and 2 billion yuan in output
value.
</P>
<P>
The project will also help bring to an end the centuries-old
problem of the weather deciding whether a harvest was a success or
failure, Zhang says.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has a water problem. Its per capita water resources
amount to one third of the national average. Liaoning was hit by 7
serious droughts in the past 5 decades and grain output has been
reduced by as much as 2 to 3.5 billion kg annually since 1978 as a
result of droughts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
