<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lowers Duty to Help Tackle Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has lowered
duty to a preferential rate of five percent for equipment related
to information technology so as to help institutions to tackle
the millennium bug problem.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae said Thursday the government
has also sponsored a number of seminars on the issue to raise
awareness among the public and private sectors so as to get them
prepared, the Daily Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury has set for itself a target of having its systems
year 2000 compliant by June 30,1999.
</P>
<P>
"This gives us only 49 weeks to implement the changes that
must be put in place by the first day of the new century," said
Nyachae.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the "bug" will have devastating effects on
the economy if corrective measures were not made in an effective
and timely manner.
</P>
<P>
"The millennium bug is seen as a national problem requiring
national attention," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If it is not possible to effectively deal with the problem
within the deadline of December 31 1999, it will be necessary to
put in place standby arrangements and perhaps recovery plans," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Financial Secretary Joseph Kinyua said the government
had set aside 500 million Shillings (some 8.4 million U.S.
Dollars) and full time personnel to tackle the millennium bug by
June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to convert government computer
services, the pension department, and the Kenya Bureau of
Statistics to become year 2000 compliant, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
