<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Top Treasury Officials Arrested on Frauds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority
(KACA) has arrested four top treasury officials over alleged
frauds involving more than 230 million Shillings (some 3.9
million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Kenya Revenue Authority Commissioner-General John Msafari,
Commissioner of Customs Samuel Chebii, Financial Secretary Joseph
Kanyi Kinyua, Director of Fiscal and Monetary Affairs Njeru
Kirira and 11 other Customs officials were arrested Thursday,
media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Magistrate Uniter Kidullah said when issuing the arrest
order that the move followed an application by the director of
the Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority (KACA), John Harun Mwau.
</P>
<P>
They were accused of defrauding the government through failure
to tax revenue on sugar and wheat imported from Brazil and
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
They are also to be charged with breaching the public trust by
fraudulently allowing 1,400 tons of uninspected sugar into the
country.
</P>
<P>
Failure to collect tax on illegal sugar imports was a key
complaint by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) when it
suspended a major loan to Kenya in July last year. The IMF has
also asked for reforming KRA.
</P>
<P>
Other IMF demands, agreed with the government in last August,
included the setting up of an independent anti-corruption
authority, reform of the energy sector and investigation of past
abuses of public funds.
</P>
<P>
KACA was set up last December under Mwau, an ex-policeman and
former presidential candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
