<HEADLINE> China Continues Effort To Join WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China is continuing its effort to
enter the World Trade Organization, according to Hu Zhaoqing, a
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation spokesman.
</P>
<P>
While giving an overview of China's foreign trade and economic
cooperation in the first half of 1998 at a news conference here
today, he pointed to consultations with WTO members like the U.S.,
the EU, Japan, and Canada, and especially the intense talks before
U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
During these talks, he said, the Chinese made several proposals
and there was some progress, but no final arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The eighth meeting of WTO's China Working Party is now being
held in Geneva. At the previous one in March and April, the
Chinese delegation submitted a list of specific tariff rates to
reduce China's average industrial tariff to 10.8 percent. This was
another significant effort on China's part to move the negotiation
process forward, Hu said. 
</P>
