<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Karst Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China is estimated to have 200
billion cubic meters of water resources in karst formations for
annual use, accounting for a quarter of the nation's subterranean
water resources.
</P>
<P>
China has a vast amount of karst formations, 1.2 million square
kilometers of which is exposed, that makes up a seventh of the
country's land area, according to the Chinese Academy of
Geological Sciences' Guilin Karst Geology Institute.
</P>
<P>
The most well-known formations are the Fenglin Karst that
covers more than 500,000 square kilometers in southern China and
that of the high and cold Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
One study has shown that there are 2,497 subterranean rivers in
southern China, with a total flow rate of 1,482 cubic meters per
second. There are also 2,450 karst fountains in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Disu subterranean river in the Du'an Yao Autonomous County
of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has been shown to have 23
main water courses over 57 kilometers. Local people have long used
the water for drinking and irrigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
