<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
Thursday rejected a request by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
for an immediate summit, with Arafat aides saying talks cannot
resume until Israel accepts the U.S. pullback proposal. Netanyahu
sent Likud coalition chairman Meir Shetrit to meet Arafat to
present the request for holding a summit so that the two leaders
could hammer out remaining differences.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian officials have admitted that they cannot count
on the Clinton administration to press Israel to yield 13 percent
of the West Bank, as originally proposed by the U.S., which rather
urges the Palestinians to compromise with Israel. A PLO
representative in the U.S. said that the U.S. has no alternative
strategy to offer, once its initiative is officially declared a
failure.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli and U.S. officials will conduct joint assessment of
the situation following Iran's missile test Wednesday. Reports
from the U.S. said that the Iran missile missed its target
in the test, but U.S. officials said they expected an
additional test of the Shihab-3 missile to be conducted soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
