<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Chinese Bank Raises Credit Line to 230b Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial and Commercial Bank
of China (ICBC), one of China's leading commercial banks, has
announced plans to raise its annual credit line for 1998 to 230
billion yuan as part an effort to expand the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Information released during a bank work conference indicated
that the new loans will include 45 billion yuan in fixed asset
loans, 30 billion yuan in housing loans, and loans totalling 30
billion yuan for small- to medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The bank also plans to expand support for infrastructure
projects and the housing sector, and will direct over half of
total fixed asset loans to the infrastructure sector.
</P>
<P>
Highways, power grids, telecommunications, and urban utilities
projects will have top priority in terms of loans, with highly
profitable renovation projects featuring the use of high
technology also receiving priority consideration for loan support.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show the granted loans totalling 22 billion
yuan to the fixed assets sector during the first half of the year,
up six billion yuan on the 1997 period. Infrastructure projects
and basic industries accounted for over half of total loans.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also pledged to intensify support for the housing
sector, one of main engines driving the national economy, and
plans to extend mortgage loans totaling some 19 billion yuan to
home buyers.
</P>
<P>
ICBC officials note that bank greatly accelerated loans
approvals during the January-June period. The bank reported
outstanding loans of 81.8 billion yuan period, up 17.3 billion
yuan on the same 1997 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
