<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh: A Country Vulnerable to Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Flood occurs in Bangladesh almost
every year and incurs heavy losses of both lives and properties
due to the country's particular geographical location and its
climatic features.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is a nation in the Ganges Delta of South Asia. Half
of its 145,000 square kilometers territory which is divided by
experts here into three parts -- the Tertiary Hill in the
southeast, the Pleistocene Uplands in the northwest and the Recent
Plains, is flat alluvial plain below 7.6 meters in elevation.
</P>
<P>
The first two parts, the Tertiary Hills and the Uplands, at
elevations of 305 meters and 9-18 meters respectively, are mostly
flood-free areas, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Recent Plains, consisting mainly of flood plains made up of
continental deposits, deltaic plains built up by both marine and
continental deposits, and the tidal plains composed predominantly
of marine deposits, are all of very low elevation with
considerable areas lying below the 3-meter contour line and all of
them taken together occupy 90 percent of the areas of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has as many as 230 rivers, the majority of which
constituting an interlocking net fall into three river systems -
the Ganges, the Brahmaputra-Jamuna and the Meghna.
</P>
<P>
The river systems shape the daily life of the people and also
bring the perennial threat of flood, according to Dr. A.K.M.
Kafiluddin, a prominent expert in the country.
</P>
<P>
Seventy to 80 percent of the country's annual rainfall
concentrates in the monsoon season, he said, when the rainfall
varies from 89 centimeters in the west to more than 152
centimeters in the northeastern and southeastern parts of
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Heavy monsoon rainfall, coinciding with the flood waters from
the upstreams of rivers and surges in the Bay of Bengal, and
coupled with the location of the major parts of the country at the
lowermost reaches of the three mighty river systems, which drain
vast basins at low altitude, make floods an annual phenomenon
here.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the major parts of the country are vulnerable to
floods due either to overtopping of the river banks by flood
waters as is the case in most flood-affected areas or to
impounding of rain waters in low-lying areas, as is the case of
coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
To reduce flood-caused losses, they said the government should
make long-term plans to deal with possible flooding in the future
instead of merely distributing relief materials.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the experts suggested the construction of upstream
storage dams, embankments and reservoirs in plains for shallow
storage, and channel improvement by dredging rivers.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed measures such as flood preparedness, a
flood-forecasting system, and community-based flood preparedness
activities like evacuation, sheltering, flood fighting,
stock-piling of food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10 million people have been affected by floods in the
country and 61 have lost their lives since the monsoon season in
the country began early this month, according to officials from
the Disaster Management and Relief Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Many of those affected have been rendered homeless, as flood
waters have wrecked 29,000 homes, partially damaged 194,000
houses, and ravaged 381,000 acres of standing crops, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The figures may rise further as more rains are expected during
the monsoon season between July and October, weather experts said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has so far sanctioned more than 4
million taka (about 85,000 U.S. dollars) and 2,481 tons of rice or
wheat together with other relief materials for the flood-stricken
population, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
