<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Resurgence in Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China reversed the temporary
decline in 1997 with a 5.53 percent rise in pledged foreign
investments to slightly over 24.2 billion US dollars during the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhaoqing, a spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), released the figures this morning
at a press conference on the development of China's foreign trade
and economic cooperation in the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of overseas funds actually used stood at 20.45
billion US dollars during that period, down 1.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
The structure of foreign investment further improved with an
increase in large projects and more projects involving European
and American partners. The average investment grew 6.4 percent to
2.5 million US dollars during the period, according to Hu.
</P>
<P>
China approved a total of 314,533 overseas-financed companies
through the end of June, with contracted foreign investment
approaching 545.37 billion US dollars, including some 242.32
billion dollars actually used.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 overseas-funded businesses have been canceled or
terminated for various reasons, with 250,000 remaining in
operation, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Hu said China will strive to attract more foreign investment
and noted that MOFTEC will sponsor seven investment
promotion fairs outside the country during 1998 as part of its
effort to attract more companies from Europe and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC's efforts during the latter half of this year will focus
on preparations for the '98 China Investment and Trade Promotion
Fair, said Hu.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say the computer network currently being
installed will offer online.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also accelerate approval procedures for major
foreign investment projects proposed by various localities
provided they comply with existing laws and regulations, according
to Hu.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts will be made to improve the investment
environment and assist existing overseas-financed businesses, said
Hu, adding that the ministry will continue to try to abolish
illicit fees and charges in order to educe burdens on enterprises
and create a better investment environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
