<HEADLINE> Sea-bed Cable in African W. Coast to be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A sea-bed cable along the western
coast of the African continent will be commissioned in June,
2000, the seventh meeting of the finance and trade team on the
sea-bed cable program of African western coast said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting which ended here Thursday discussed how
to make profit from the cable and the ways of attracting other
countries to join the project.
</P>
<P>
The program which costs 547 million U.S. Dollars will be
financed by 13 countries -- Angola, South Africa, Benin, Cote
d'Ivoire, Cameroun, Gabon, Niger, Senegal, Liberia, Namibia,
Nigeria, Ghana and Guinea, and Angola promises to pay 20 million.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Taiko Company is entitled to survey the geographic
situation of the African western coast as of next week, choose
the position to lay the sea-bed cable and provide a feasibility
report to the participating countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., Portugal, Britain, Italy, Japan Malaysia, India and
Mauritius are among the countries which have expressed interest
in the project.
</P>
<P>
The project will improve the telecommunications links of
Africa with countries in other parts of the world and lower their
costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
