<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Signs Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday signed the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) at the United Nations
headquarters in New York, according to a statement issued here by
its foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will soon take the necessary steps to ratify the
treaty, signed by its Permanent Representative to the United
Nations Hasmy Agam, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the CTBT is in consonance with Malaysia's firm
commitment to the goals of general and complete disarmament. It is
also a reaffirmation of Malaysia's consistent support towards all
international efforts aimed at nuclear disarmament and
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that as part of the International Monitoring
System of the Treaty, Malaysia will be hosting a radionuclide
monitoring station and the Malaysia Institute of Nuclear
Technology Research will act as the national agency for overseeing
the implementation of the requirements of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The CTBT, opened for signature on September 24, 1996, bans all
nuclear weapon test explosions and any other nuclear explosion and
provides a verification regime that consists of an International
Monitoring System, consultation and clarification, on-site
inspections and confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
To date, 150 countries including Malaysia have signed the
treaty and 15 countries have ratified it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Postal Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The city of Tianjin has
established a postal museum for the 120th anniversary of China's
first stamp, which was issued in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) issued stamps bearing a dragon
design in Tianjin in July of 1878, three months after the imperial
court decided to try out a modern postal service in six cities.
</P>
<P>
The museum provides a history of China's postal service from
ancient courier stations to the modern age and electronic postal
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
