<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of Japanese Ruling Party Chief, Obuchi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Keizo Obuchi is elected as the new
president of the Japanese ruling Liberal Democratic Party Friday
afternoon with 225 votes of the 414 ballots.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, attracted a great deal of attention when as Chief
Cabinet Secretary he gave a news conference to announce Japan's
new era, "Heisei," shortly after Emperor Showa died in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has been elected to the House of Representatives for 12
times since he was first elected to the lower chamber at age of 26
in Gunman Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi advanced his political career in the most powerful
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) faction of former Prime Minister
Kakuei Tanaka, who is known for creating a period of historic
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Obuchi helped Noboru Takeshita set up his new
faction. Takeshita split from Tanaka faction and served as prime
minister from 1987 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
As one of the seven closest aides to Takeshita, Obuchi
succeeded the Takeshita faction and set up his own faction, which
became the largest group within the LDP.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is very adept at political adjustment and
building a consensus.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi racked up almost no economic experience as state
minister in charge of the Prime Minister's Office under the late
Prime Minister Masayoshi Ohira from 1979 to 1980 and chief cabinet
secretary under former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita from 1987
to 1989.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he has focused on LDP business as the party's
secretary general and vice president.
</P>
<P>
As leader of the largest LDP faction, Obuchi tolerated the
fielding of Ryutaro Hashimoto from his camp in 1995 as candidate
for LDP president, a move that earned him the tag of being "nice."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Obuchi are of the same age and they entered the
lower house together in 1963.
</P>
<P>
As foreign minister in Hashimoto's second cabinet, Obuchi
pressed for the signing of a global treaty to ban antipersonnel
land mines, and worked extensively to improve ties with Russia
toward signing a peace treaty by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
While he has earned a good reputation in foreign policy, Obuchi
has yet to build a reputation in domestic affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
