<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Foreign Ministers Pay Courtesy Call on Estrada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the nine
member countries of the Association of the Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) here Friday paid a courtesy call on Philippine President
Joseph Estrada before the opening of the 31st ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting (AMM).
</P>
<P>
Touching on the Asian financial crisis, Estrada told the
ministers that he was heartened that ASEAN had stood by these
challenges and had jointly instituted measures to cushion the
impact of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his support for the various measures taken to
fight the economic and financial crisis, such as the establishment
of the ASEAN monitoring mechanism which is being working out by
the Asian Development Bank and the ASEAN Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he was particularly interested in ASEAN's
concerted action to cushion the impact of the crisis, commenting
Malaysia and the Philippines for entering into an agreement on the
use of their currencies in intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
The President also reiterated that his administration was
committed to continuing the market-based economic policies of the
previous Fidel Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada added that his government had resolved to adhere to the
original schedule of the Common Effective Preferential Tariff
Reduction, according to which ASEAN must cut its tariffs to less
than five percent by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
He said the Philippines would also adhere to the realization of
the ASEAN Free Trade Area, the full implementation of the ASEAN
Industrial Cooperation and the realization of the ASEAN Investment
Area, three of the most important development and cooperation
projects in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada also emphasized the importance of agreeing
on a concerted action and cooperative mechanism with ASEAN to
fight drugs.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending the 31st AMM are expected to sign a
joint declaration which aims to build ASEAN into a region free
from illicit drug production, abuse and trafficking by the year
2020.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers are namely Prince Mohamad Bolkiah of
Brunei Darussalam, Ali Alatas of Indonesia, Somsawat Lengsavad of
Laos, Adbullah Ahmad Badawi of Malaysia, U Ohn Gyaw of Myanmar,
Shunmugam Jayakumar of Singapore, Surin Pitsuwan of Thailand,
Nguyen Manh Cam of Vietnam and Domingo Siazon of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Chem Widhaya, permanent secretary of Cambodia, Papua New Guinea
Foreign Minister Roy Yaki and ASEAN Secretary General Rodolfo
Severino also attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
