<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting  Opens in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) opened its 31st ministerial meeting here Friday to
discuss a number of issues affecting the region, with Philippine
President Joseph Estrada calling for restoring financial and
economic stability and for a true ASEAN community.
</P>
<P>
Presiding over the opening session, President Estrada called
restoration of financial and economic stability in the region "our
immediate concern."
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN's resilience has been put under severe strain by the
financial crisis sweeping across Asia," he said. "Mothballed
assembly lines and padlocked factory doors tell of real suffering
afflicting our peoples. Millions have already lost their jobs and
so many more are going hungry."
</P>
<P>
Some ASEAN countries, particularly Indonesia and Thailand, have
been hit hard by the financial crisis which broke out in July last
year after their currencies have devalued by a big margin, leading
to bank and factory closures and massive layoffs of workers.
</P>
<P>
Noting that ASEAN governments have taken and continue to take
measures to address the problems, Estrada also urged other
countries to help by achieving economic recovery or providing
greater market access to ASEAN products.
</P>
<P>
But the president stressed that despite the present crisis,
ASEAN, which groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, "will move
surely toward greater integration."
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN integration will redound to the benefit of all," he
declared. "And it will only happen if we move together toward
greater total convergence, in our economic life and beyond."
</P>
<P>
He called on member countries to "be open to one another and
freely and candidly exchange views no matter how controversial the
issue." "Only by being open can we truly appreciated what unites
or divides us. Only by talking freely and candidly can we rise and
build and prosper together."
</P>
<P>
Attending Friday's open session are foreign ministers from the
nine ASEAN member countries and Papua New Guinea, an observer
country, and the permanent secretary of the Foreign Ministry of
Cambodia, which also enjoys observer status in the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting, foreign
ministers from the member countries are expected to discuss the
ongoing Asian financial crisis and measures to deal with its
social impacts, the forthcoming Cambodian elections, nuclear
proliferation in South Asia, fight against transnational crimes
and other important issues.
</P>
<P>
The AMM is an annual event responsible for the formulation of
policy guidelines and coordination of ASEAN activities.
</P>
<P>
At this year's meeting, the ministers are also expected to
discuss and decide whether there will be a change in ASEAN's
policy from "non-interference" to "flexible engagement."
</P>
<P>
Thailand raised the idea of "flexible engagement," which means
that when domestic developments in a country have had positive or
adverse effects on other ASEAN nations, these nations can give
advice to or press the said country to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, ASEAN's rotating chairman this year, supports
the new proposal. However, all the other ASEAN members are opposed
to the idea.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar made it clear earlier
that "there is no need to change the principle of
non-interference," which he described as "a well-tested principle
which has served ASEAN well." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Affects More People in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- More Bangladeshi people have been
affected by flood as the water levels of major rivers in the
country are still on the rise submerging more areas.
</P>
<P>
About one in every 12 people of Bangladesh's over-120 million
population has been affected by flood since the monsoon season
began in the country in early July, and the death toll from flood
rose to 61 as of Thursday night, according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's 64 districts, 54 have been affected, with
standing crops on 381,000 acres of land ravaged, 29,000 homes
wrecked and 194,000 houses partially damaged by monsoon floods,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,100 heads of cattle were missing, 1,274 kilometers of
roads and 1409 kilometers of embankments were damaged by flood.
</P>
<P>
District administrations of affected areas were still assessing
the extent of losses, the reports said. "A clear picture is
expected within a few days," a Relief Control Room officials said.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the Army had been placed on alert as part
of the contingency measure to carry out sudden evacuation
operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far sanctioned more than 4 million (about
85,000 U.S. dollars) and 2,481 tons of rice or wheat together with
other relief materials for the flood-stricken population.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation might worsen in central Bangladesh as
rivers in the region continued to rise above their red marks,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Seventy to 80 percent of the country's annual rainfall
concentrates in the monsoon seasons between May and September,
which, combined with its particular geographical features, often
causes flood, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
