<HEADLINE> Rainy Season May Delay 2002 World Cup by Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korean soccer officials said
Friday they will coordiante with co-host Japan in the timing of
the 2002 World Cup finals as its rainy season may halt the flow of
the quadrennial sports extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Football Association admitted that it is likely to
reschedule the timing as its rainy season could cause problems if
the World Cup finals sticks to its normal time in June and July.
</P>
<P>
But, there was no formal request to be put forward to the
sport's world governing body FIFA to postpone the tournament to
September or October, and the topic was only raised informally
during the last edition in France last month.
</P>
<P>
The Korean official who requested anonymity, said South Korea
and Japan will jointly decide the timing of the event by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The schedule has to be submitted to FIFA by May 15 next year.
</P>
<P>
"It is true we will discuss the possibility of rescheduling
games since it will be the rainy season here, but there are lots
of factors that have to be considered," he said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem will be rescheduling the leagues in Europe
and South America. Besides, South Korea will also host the Asian
Games in Pusan in late 2002.
</P>
<P>
"Rain is a problem in the June-July season, but we have to
consider may other factors. At the moment, we don't even know
ourselves if the games should be rescheduled or not."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the official said that South Korea was in no mood to
back out of the tournament despite its economic crisis although
the host cities may be reduced from 10 to six. 
</P>
</TEXT>
