<HEADLINE> Chinese Divers Steal Limelight at Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 23 (Xinhua) -- China's world champions Sun
Shuwei and Tian Liang took the highlight of the day when they
outdived the other world big names with a huge margin to win the
men's 10-meter platform synchronized gold medal at the Goodwill
Games here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Huang Xu added another gold for China by winning the men's
parallel bars while Belarus' all-around champion Ivan Ivankov put
the men's gymnastics horizontal bar gold into his pocket.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Alina Kabayeva displayed grace and beauty in the
women's rhythmic gymnastics to land the all-around title. The
day's another gold was grabbed by Irina Lashko of Russia in the
women's one-meter springboard.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pair Sun and Tian combined to chalk up 91.08
points, the day's highest score, in their final dive, accumulating
a total of 344.64 points for the gold.
</P>
<P>
Eduardo Rueda and Fernando Platas of Merxico overtook Alexandr
Varlamov and Igor Loukashin of Russia in their last actions,
edging the European runners-up for the silver, with a score of
308.10 to the Russian pair's 304.98.
</P>
<P>
World champion Lashko held off two Chinese divers to snatch the
title with a score of 278.25 points.
</P>
<P>
China's Guo Jingjing, 1995 World Cup winner and world platform
runner-up this year, improved her place round after round,
wrapping up second position with 270.93 points ahead of teammate
Zhang Jing, who collected 270.15.
</P>
<P>
The men's event was a totally Chinese show. Sun, 1992 Olympic
platform winner, and Tian, World Cup platform champion this year,
led all the way through the five-round final.
</P>
<P>
The Mexico duo put up a brilliant performance on their last
outing, napping the Russians by three points.
</P>
<P>
"We were not nervous at all. We only forcused our attention on
the dives. I think our last dives deserved that high score," Sun
said.
</P>
<P>
"I have fulfilled my first goal here, my next goal is to win
the individual platform. I will try my best to do that," Tian
claimed after winning the first gold for China at the Games.
</P>
<P>
The women's one-meter springboard competition was dominated by
Lashko throughout. The 25-year-old veteran, winner of the 1991
World Cup and silver medalist in the 1992 and 1996 Olympics, made
consistent fine performance in all her five dives.
</P>
<P>
She had a perfect final dive - reverse one and a half plus
somersaults in pike - which brought her the highest score of 60.48.
</P>
<P>
At a post-race press conference, Lashko said: "I felt fine
during the competition. My favorite dive was my fifth dive. The
facility is nice but the air and pool temperature is cold."
</P>
<P>
Guo, 16, said: "I am happy about the silver finish. I hope I
can do better in the other events."
</P>
<P>
Huang, a member of the Chinese winning team at last year's
world championships, stepped out of the shadow of the tragic
injury to his teammate Sang Lan, collecting 9.725 points ahead of
Ivankov, who scored 9.700, and Alexei Bondarenko, also from
Russia, 9.650.
</P>
<P>
Ivankov shone in the horizontal bar final with a 9.725-point
win over his teammate Alexei Nemov, reigning world and European
champion in floor exercises, and Sergei Fedorchenko of Kazkastan.
Nemov raked up 9.650 to Fedorchenko's 9.525.
</P>
<P>
Kabayeva ranked first in all the four events to finish overall
first with 39.781 points.
</P>
<P>
In the men's basketball semifinals, Australia beat defending
champions Puerto Rico 86-74, while the United States downed
Lithuania 89-76. Australia will meet the host team in the showdown
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
In the beach volleyball contest which started today, Canada's
John Child and Mark Heese beat Sinjin Smith and Ricci Luyties of
the United States 15-5, while Brazil's Para and Guiherme thrashed
Karch Kiraly and Adam Johnson of the United States 15-3 in group A.
</P>
<P>
Lee Zahner teamed with Julien Prosser gave Australia a victory
over Paul Laciga and Martin Laciga of Switzerland 15-3, and
Esteban Martinez and Martin Conde of Argentina edged Jan Kvalheim
and Bjorn Maaseide of Norway 16-14 in group B. 
</P>
</TEXT>
