<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Raises Doubt Over Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jardine Fleming Thanakom Securities said in a study revealed
Friday that at least 1.124 trillion baht (25 billion U.S. dollars)
is required for the privatization of corporations listed on the
Stock Exchange of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Korn Chatikavanij, managing director of the institute, said
the corporations stand very little chance in meeting
recapitalization targets amid the present liquidity crunch.
</P>
<P>
After the baht floated on July 2 last year, debt to equity has
increased from 100 percent to 250 percent at the moment, with the
baht at 40 to 41 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
This could be a big burden for the government which earlier
made a commitment with foreign creditors to guarantee all private
sector debts.
</P>
<P>
Currently, corporations, especially financial institutions,
can only absorb damages up to 6.6 percent as most firms have run
up 30-35 percent of non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Korn suggested that both local and foreign creditors reach a
compromise on some of the loans to Thai firms to help them survive
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In addition, capital inflow through foreign direct investment
to Thailand remained lower than expected, accounting for only 12
percent of total new capital required, compared with 93 percent in
Malaysia and 42 percent in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Piyasvasti Amranand, secretary general of the National Energy
Policy Office (NEPO), said the study reflects a need for the
government to set clear measures in the privatization plan.
</P>
<P>
For the energy sector, NEPO expects to gain 100 billion baht
(2.5 billion dollars) from selling shares of companies, including
the government's stake in Esso (Thailand). Next year, the
government will privatize the Ratchaburi power plant project and
Bangchak Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Piyasvasti, however, said the new capital is insufficient to
help reduce the burden, and the government has to accelerate the
privatization process of other state units including Thai Airways
International and Telephone Organization of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the privatization process cannot solve the
country's financial problems, so the government has to improve
exports while corporations have to rush into debt restructuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
