<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Ministers Gather in Portugal on Marine Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- European environment ministers
signed the Sintra Declaration Thursday in Sintra, Portugal, which
is intended to strengthen environmental protection over the
northeast Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from all 15 European Union countries and
representatives from 14 official and unofficial organizations
gathered in Sintra for two days to discuss protection for the
great variety of marine life, to reduce the discharge of
radioactive waste from nuclear companies, and to properly
dismantle decommissioned old oil rigs.
</P>
<P>
The dismantling of 40 of the largest offshore installations,
each weighing more than 10,000 tons, will depend on a case-by-case
technical feasibility study, the ministers said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The declaration on reducing discharges of radioactive waste to
close to zero by 2020 was believed one of the achievements in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The Sintra Declaration, signed by the 15 member countries of
the Convention for the Protection of the Marine Environment of the
Northeast Atlantic, was described as of great significance in
reducing marine pollution.
</P>
<P>
The convention became effective on March 25. The two-day Sintra
conference was the first ministerial meeting of the organization;
it ended Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
