<HEADLINE> Airport Resumes Full Service in Catania, Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The airport of Fontanarossa in the
Sicilian city of Catania, Italy, has resumed full service from
1:00 pm Thursday after temporary closure due to the volcano ashes
fallen on the runways.
</P>
<P>
Vitreous ashes produced by a volcano eruption of Mount Etna
fell on the runways and forced the airport to close at 10:00 pm
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Sicilian volcano intensified its activity early Wednesday
afternoon and by Wednesday evening the runways were already
covered by a fine glossy dust which could have caused problems for
airplane landing and taking off.
</P>
<P>
The local volcanology institute said that the activity of Mount
Etna was a temporary phenomenon and should not be a cause of
concern.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, hundreds of similar eruptions on Mount
Etna were registered by the centre.
</P>
<P>
Experts there said that although such activity indicates that
the volcano is active, it is not a sign of an imminent full scale
eruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
