<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Blames Economic Woes on Outside Factors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) has blamed outside factors such as transformation
in the global financial system for the economic woes which have
been plaguing the region since July last year.
</P>
<P>
"Much of the storm that has ravaged ASEAN's economies
originated outside the region," said ASEAN Secretary-General
Rodolfo Severino in a report to the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
(AMM) which began here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the light of the transformation in the global
financial system wrought by globalization and abetted by massive,
uncontrolled and lightning-fast capital movements, moves are being
made to draw up a new architecture for the international financial
system.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN would do well to ensure that it makes a collective
contribution, the product of deep and rigorous thought and
discussion, to this new architecture," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise," he warned, "others will be deciding, once again,
the economic destiny of Southeast Asia, to the peril of the region
and its people."
</P>
<P>
Severino pointed out that at the heart of ASEAN's concern is
the impact of the financial and economic crisis on its people's
lives, particularly in terms of their livelihood and employment.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the loss of jobs and a general reduction of
purchasing power, he said, the incidence of poverty has gone up in
many countries and in some, health care has been impaired, food
shortages have arisen and children have been forced to drop out of
school. "This has enormous implications for the future," he
declared. "Unless this trend is reversed rapidly, the significant
gains achieved by ASEAN economies during the past two decades
could be negated very quickly."
</P>
<P>
Some members of ASEAN, which groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam, used to be the fastest growing economies in the world
before the financial crisis hit the region.
</P>
<P>
Severino called for efforts to obtain more funds and assistance
for these countries to address the impact of the crisis, including
active ASEAN involvement in the use of funds from the World Bank
and the Asia-Europe meeting fund.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the use of ASEAN currencies for the settlement of
intra-ASEAN trade, the ASEAN secretary-general said the modalities
for carrying this out are to be agreed upon between the trading
partners concerned and are currently being worked out between
Malaysia and the Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia, Malaysia and
Thailand as well as Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The use of local currencies to settle trade between ASEAN
members was first proposed by Malaysia to reduce dependence on the
U.S. dollar after regional currencies suffered heavy devaluation
during the financial crisis and the proposal later won the support
of finance ministers of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
However, Severino made it clear that "this is not about a
single ASEAN currency. It is not a panacea. But it should help
relieve the pressure on ASEAN countries to obtain hard currency,
encourage them to trade with one another and stimulate economic
activity in general."
</P>
<P>
He urged that ASEAN should expedite the process of concluding
the necessary bilateral payments arrangements between member
countries and of devising measures to encourage ASEAN traders to
use ASEAN currencies in the settlement of their trade between
themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Pays Attention to Potency of Traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, July 24 (Xinhua)-- Myanmar is paying attention to
conservation and promotion of the potency of genuine traditional
medicines and is endeavoring to turn out drug inspectors in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A training course of traditional medicine drug inspectors, the
first of its kind, is being conducted here, jointly sponsored by
Traditional Medicine Department of the Myanmar Ministry of Health
and the World Health Organization, the official newspaper the New
Light of Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar enacted the Traditional Medicine Law in July 1996 to
uplift the potency of indigenous medicine and to ensure safety for
users, issuing patents and licenses to entrepreneurs and testing
traditional medicines in advanced laboratories.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been 700 local entrepreneurs permitted to
produce and sell their medicinal products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar have used traditional medicines since ancient times
which are still popular among people both in urban and rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there were three indigenous
hospitals and 194 dispensaries with more than 400 practitioners in
 Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
