<HEADLINE> FIVB Opposes Bribery in Volleyball Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- FIVB president Ruben Acosta said Thursday that
his organization was concerned on the bribery allegations and would pursue
necessary actions should on-going investigations justified the accusations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement from Lausanne about the recent allegations of bribery
concerning the 1993 World Grand Prix match between Japan and Germany in Chinese
Taipei, Acosta said "we have just heard of these reports. Of course, FIVB is
totally against such practice which would violate all principles attached to
our sport."
</P>
<P>
The volleyball president said "primary evidence shows there seems to be no
truth to these rumors, and the Japanese Volleyball Association is conducting a
full investigation with our support."
</P>
<P>
"We will take the necessary action if these allegations prove to be true and
equally we will also act against those responsible for spreading malicious
stories should the allegations be proved false," Acosta said.
</P>
<P>
"These latest incidents may be a new episode of an organized series of
undeserved attacks on the integrity of the Japanese Volleyball Association, and
FIVB has full confidence in the outcome of this affair," he said.
</P>
<P>
The article originally published in the July 17th edition of the Japanese
newspaper Sankei Shimbun claimed that the coach of the 1993 Japanese women's
Grand Prix team offered their German opponents 1 million Yen (7,140 US dollars)
to throw their match in Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The accused Japanese coach has denied the allegations, as has his German
counterpart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
