<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Leader Urges Kosovo Conflicting Parties to Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana on Thursday urged the conflicting parties of Kosovo to sit
down and talk, suggesting that NATO may force them to quit
fighting otherwise.
</P>
<P>
Now they have the last chance to do it, Solana,
ending his two-day visit to Macedonia, said at a joint press
conference with Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov in Ohrid near
the Albania-Macedonia border.
</P>
<P>
Crisis in Kosovo could only be solved through political and
diplomatic means, said Solana.
</P>
<P>
But, he added, NATO may take measures to force the conflicting
parties to stop if necessary, without making clear what
measures NATO might take.
</P>
<P>
It's not NATO's business to find a permanent settlement to the
Kosovo crisis, Solana noted, but NATO must make efforts to help
find a political solution.
</P>
<P>
If NATO has to act, Solana said, its task is to stop the
fighting, but it will not act from Macedonia's territory.
</P>
<P>
Solana and President Gligorov both spoke highly of the good
relations between the Republic of Macedonia and NATO, and the
latter re-expressed his country's desire to join the
organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
