<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Guyana to Settle Border Dispute Via Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Venezuela and
Guyana reiterated here Thursday that their two countries would
settle their border dispute through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera Rodrigues and Guyanan
President Janet Rosenberg made the comment in a joint statement
released at the end of Rosenberg's visit to Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two countries have agreed to settle the
sovereignty issue of the disputed area of Essequibo through the
mediation of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
They will also develop friendly relations and cooperation in
social, economic, cultural, health, and environmental areas, the
statement affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also strengthen cooperation in fighting
drug abuse and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
They will also form a working panel soon to cooperate in
exploring and developing ocean resources, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also expand cooperation between their
armed forces, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Rosenberg arrived here Tuesday for a three-day official
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
