<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Increase Makes Up for China's  Losses in Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua)-- China's exports to the United
States and other continents have surged in the first five months
this year, a high-ranking official with the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Co-operation (MOFTEC) said this morning.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhaoqing, spokesman for the MOFTEC, said that the
achievements, a result of the strategy of market diversification,
have worked effectively to secure an export growth for the first
half of 1998, "making up in part for the country's losses caused
by the Asian financial crisis".
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remark at a press conference sponsored by the
MOFTEC to provide an overview of China's foreign trade and economic
cooperation in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, between January and May, China's
exports to the European Union (EU) rose by 25.5 percent, to the
United States, by 18.1 percent; and to Africa, Latin America and
Oceania, by 44.7 percent, 38.1 per cent and 15.2 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The growth rates are all above those of last year," said Hu,
adding that the MOFTEC has also stepped up efforts to diversify
the sources of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, contractual foreign investments from
the EU grew by 86.64 percent and those from the United States by
80.85 percent during that period.
</P>
<P>
China's balance of payment is in good shape, and its foreign
exchanges reserves continued to rise during the first half of this
year, when imports and exports totaled 151.4 billion U.S. dollars,
up 5.2 percent from the same period 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of this, exports stood at 87 billion U.S. dollars and imports
at 64.4 billion U.S. dollars, up 7.6 percent and 2.2 percent
respectively. That led to a trade surplus of 22.6 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
