<HEADLINE> Thailand Turns Trade Deficit Into Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The surplus stood in baht terms at 225.8 billion baht, compared
with a deficit of 173.7 billion baht in the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The baht is currently traded at about 40-41 to the dollars
compared with 25 baht to the dollar before July 2, last year.
</P>
<P>
Export surged by 60.7 percent in baht terms to 1,163 billion
baht, while imports increased by 4.6 percent to 937.7 billion
baht.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 exports were computers, electical appliance,
garments, rubber products, electric circuits, rice, gems and
jewelry, plastic products, canned seafood and frozen shrimps.
</P>
<P>
The main imports were electrical and other machinery,
chemicals, electric circuits, oil, computers, steel product,
electrical appliances, iron and steel, textiles.
</P>
<P>
in June, exports were worth 180 billion baht, up by 8 percent
in baht terms on those for the same month of last year, while
imports were worth 146 billion baht, up by 10.9 percent. 
</P>
