<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop Weed Killer-Proof Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have developed
a type rice that is not affected by weed-killer through gene
splicing.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Institute of Rice injected altered genes
into rice to develop the new strain, and then tested the shoots
against weed killer that killed all the weeds while the rice
remained unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Because of the use of direct seeding techniques on China's 2
million hectares of rice paddies, weeds are increasingly becoming
a headache for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show 15 billion kilograms of grain going to waste
each year because of weeds and 2 to 3 billion working days spent
annually just getting rid of weeds from the farmland.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in various parts of the world have already used
similar gene splicing on corn, rapeseed, and soybeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
