<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Launch Debt Restructuring Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank plans to
launch the Indonesian Debt Restructuring Agency (INDRA) on August
3 to help restructure corporate debt and lend support to the
beleaguered rupiah, the Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
INDRA would target 2,000 indebted local companies which
together owe 64 billion U.S. dollars to foreign creditors, Bank
Indonesia (BI) Director Dono Iskandar told reporters at the
central bank's office here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate aim of INDRA is to reduce pressure on the rupiah
by reducing the U.S. dollar demand of private-sector corporations.
</P>
<P>
"The more companies that join INDRA, the stronger the rupiah
will become. If the rupiah strengthens then most of our economic
problems, like food, electricity and fuel subsidies, will be
automatically solved," Dono said.
</P>
<P>
INDRA, set up under a debt rescheduling agreement reached in
Frankfurt, Germany, is a government institution under the
supervision of the central bank. The agreement was signed by BI
and 13 foreign banks on June 4.
</P>
<P>
Dono acknowledged that many Indonesian companies became
technically unable to repay their debt when the rupiah fell
sharply early this year. It is now hovering at around 14,000
rupiah to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, he was still optimistic that Indonesian companies
would join the debt plan, noting that otherwise they would be
declared bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
According to BI, Indonesia's total overseas obligations were
comprised of 54.4 billion U.S. dollars in long-term government
debt and 83.6 billion U.S. dollars in debt belonging to the
private sector and state-owned companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Companies Benefitting From Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Shangri-la Hotel is a
major residence for visiting foreign businessmen, but few people
know that its largest stake-holder is Minmetals Development
Co. Ltd., China's largest mineral and metals exporter.
</P>
<P>
The company is also the second largest stockholder of Xiamen
Tungsten Company, the world's largest tungsten manufacturer. Since
it was listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange in May 1997, the
company has invested 624 million yuan raised on the stock market
in various areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it did 1.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of import and
export business and had domestic sales of 1.3 billion yuan and 230
million yuan in profits.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Board Miao Gengshu explains that issuing shares
has contributed to this development.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more Chinese companies have been listed on the
stock market and more are expected to do so to raise funds and
increase their competitiveness. One government plan calls for at
least one foreign trade company from each province, municipality
or ethnic autonomous region issuing stocks by the year 2000,
according to Liu Shan, Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The first year for a foreign trade company to issue shares was
1993. Now, 19 Chinese foreign trade companies have been listed on
the stock market where they have raised more than 4 billion yuan,
most of which has been put into areas encouraged by the government
like agriculture, communications and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese foreign trade companies used to be regarded
as 'foreign currency earners'," Liu says, "but now they are asked
to be profit-makers."
</P>
<P>
All these listed companies are doing better on average than the
700 listed Chinese firms and many have expanded their business at
low cost and are getting an increasingly large share on the
capital market.
</P>
<P>
Some local analysts say that listing the companies demonstrates
the trade sector's ability to grow by changing from the previous
exports and imports, even though the numbers are still small. The
analysts say that the stock market should be looked at by more
foreign trade companies.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 10,000 foreign trade companies, which did
325 billion U.S. dollars worth of imports and exports in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Declare World-First Cell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A team of Australian scientists
announced here Friday that they have achieved a world-first
advance by describing the structure of a vital receptor found on
the surface of the body cells of all animals, including humans.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery, reported in this week's issue of the
international scientific journal Nature, has major implications
for our understanding of the mechanism behind growth and
development, and diseases such as diabetes and many forms of
cancer," the Commonwealth Scientific, Industrial Research
Organization (CSIRO), Australia's leading research body, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The team's goal was to understand the atomic structure of a
particular family of receptors, sites on the cell surface which
detect chemical messengers such as insulin, insulin-like growth
factor (IGF) and epidermal growth factor (EGF), CSIRO said.
</P>
<P>
Receptors are vital links in the body's command chain.
Messenger chemicals like hormones and growth factors attach and
switch on their special receptor, which in turns commands the cell
to perform particular tasks, such as to grow or to process sugar.
</P>
<P>
CSIRO described the team as the first in the world to clarify
the structure of the half of the IGF receptor, marking a major
scientific milestone in a field of research that has been running
since the late 1960s when the 3 dimensional structure of insulin
was determined.
</P>
<P>
"The IGF, insulin and EGF receptors are all in the same family
and their structures are expected to be 90 percent similar, so
understanding the crystal structure of the IGF receptor helps us
to understand most of the structure of all three," explained Colin
Ward of CSIRO Molecular Science.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ward and Tom Garrett of the Biomolecular Research
Institute in Melbourne led the team.
</P>
<P>
"IGF is important to the body's normal growth and development,
but when it gets out of control it can also cause the growth of
cancer cells".
</P>
<P>
"We hope this work in time will lead to a better understanding
of ways to control certain cancers," Ward said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Provides Development Assistance to ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) committed here Friday to provide an assistance of
six million U.S. dollars to the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) for various development projects in the region.
</P>
<P>
UNDP Assistant Administrator Nay Htun and ASEAN Secretary
General Rodolfo Severino signed the letter of intent on the
assistance right before the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting opens
here.
</P>
<P>
The fund will support various development projects in the
Southeast Asian region over the next four years. Special
arrangements have been made under this scheme to enable the region
to address the financial and economic crisis and revive the
crippled economies.
</P>
<P>
Social problems resulting from the economic crisis, such as
poverty and unemployment and environmental pollution, in
particular the transboundary haze caused by forest fires in the
region, will also be tackled under these special arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has supported several of ASEAN's development projects
since ASEAN's birth in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
