<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's LDP to Elect New President Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 Kyodo - Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP) is set to elect a new president Friday afternoon with
Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi taking the lead over two other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
The new LDP president is expected to replace outgoing Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who announced his resignation
July 13 after the LDP's devastating defeat in the July 12 House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, is believed to have secured the backing of about
200 of the 414 eligible voters, including his own 92-member
faction, and more than half the members of three key groups within
the LDP.
</P>
<P>
The other two candidates in the race are former chief cabinet
secretary Seiroku Kajiyama and Health and Welfare Minister
Junichiro Koizumi.
</P>
<P>
Voting by secret ballot will take place at 14:00 local time
(0500 GMT) at the LDP's headquarters in Tokyo. The eligible voters
comprise 367 LDP Diet (parliament) members and 47 prefectural
representatives of the party's local branches.
</P>
<P>
If none of the candidates wins a majority, or 208 votes, in the
first round of voting, a run-off ballot will take place between
the top two candidates.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama, 72, and Koizumi, 56, hope to prevent Obuchi from
winning a majority in the first round of voting, thus ensuring a
second ballot.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama left the Obuchi faction after declaring his
candidacy. He is favored by some Japanese business leaders who
believe he can lift Japan out of its economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Koizumi is fielded by the second largest bloc in the LDP,
headed by former Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka. Koizumi is
supported by many of the LDP's younger lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
If Obuchi fails to secure a majority in the first round, a
Koizumi-Kajiyama alliance is unlikely, assuring Obuchi of victory
in a runoff, LDP sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
