<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to Meet Creditors On Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) will meet
with its creditor-banks Friday to discuss the impact of the
employees' strike on the recovery program being drafted for the
beleaguered and debt-ridden airline.
</P>
<P>
Perfector Yasay, chairman of the Philippine Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC), said the meeting with creditor-banks
will push through Friday due to its critical importance. Yasay is
heading a three-member hearing panel handling the rehabilitation
case of PAL.
</P>
<P>
"We have to meet so that we can discuss the viability of
rehabilitating Philippine Airlines," Yasay was quoted as saying by
the newspaper Today.
</P>
<P>
He added that the SEC will have to study carefully the impact
of the two-day strike launched by PAL ground crew Wednesday as the
PAL management has expressed a desire to shut down its operations
if it continues to post huge losses.
</P>
<P>
The SEC will have no other alternative but to allow the airline
to close down as long as the creditors agree to its decision, he
said.
</P>
<P>
PAL, the national flag carrier which has been making losses
during the past 12 years, has a total of 85.1 billion pesos in
liabilities, including capital leases, long-term debt, accrued
expenses, short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
PAL has asked the SEC to grant it a 60-day extension of the
deadline for a viable rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
The PAL Employees Association (PALEA) went on a nationwide
strike early Wednesday morning as talks with the management being
mediated by the labor department bogged down.
</P>
<P>
The union is demanding the management re-hire 5,000 employees
who were fired last month under a downsizing program.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management was forced to massively downsize its
operations to survive an indefinite strike staged by its
625-strong pilots' union on June 5. The crippling pilots' strike
lasted 22 days, plunging the already financially-troubled airline
into a deeper financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
