<HEADLINE> Population Shrinks in Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The population in eastern Europe,
including Russia, has been shrinking over the past decade, an
article in the July 23 edition of the Standard, a local newspaper,
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The article, bylined by the head of Bulgaria's Population
Research Institute, said that all the former Warsaw Pact nations,
excluding Poland, have reported smaller populations in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria had a birth rate of 0.77 percent, against a 1.47
percent death rate, a record low in history.
</P>
<P>
Unfavorable economic conditions have caused more families in
this region to bear less children, the article concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
