<HEADLINE> Return on Investment at Indonesian State Firms Below </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The average return on investment
in the 160 Indonesian state companies was only 2.68 percent, a
minister was quoted by local press Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the state companies get a return below the cost of
capital and their contribution to the state's earnings is very
small," Minister for the Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri
Abeng told members of the House of Representatives Commission V
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the low returns were one of the three main
obstacles faced by his ministry in restructuring state firms.
</P>
<P>
"The second is the resistance of management to privatization
and the third is the monetary crisis, which is causing financial
problems for state firms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abeng gave as an example the losses suffered by the state
electricity utility PT Perusahaan Listrik Negara (PLN) as a result
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The company booked a net profit of 1.2 trillion rupiah (120
million U.S. dollars) in 1996, but last year it recorded losses of
0.6 trillion rupiah and its position worsened in the first
semester of this year with reported losses of 6.5 trillion rupiah
(650 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"If we do nothing about it, the losses will be 14.7 trillion
rupiah (1.47 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of the year...
That's why the board of directors at PLN must be replaced," Abeng
said.
</P>
<P>
PLN's largest problem is that it agreed to buy too much
electricity from independent power producers at inflated rates.
That has left it with a power glut. It also agreed to pay in U.S.
dollars, even though it sells all its electricity in rupiah, the
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
