<HEADLINE> Changchun Promotes Nongovernmental Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Projections call for
nongovernmental businesses to account a third of the GDP in
Changchun, capital of Jilin Province, in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Related businesses will also account for 33 percent of the
city's total fixed capital and tax revenues by the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
The city enjoys a large labor force and abundant resources,
with the constantly improving urban infrastructure, market system
and investment environment providing a solid foundation for the
expansion of the nongovernmental business sector.
</P>
<P>
The city's total number of self-employed households grew
4.5-fold to 241,000 by the end of last year, with the number of
private firms growing 16.9-fold to 6,189 ventures on the 1995
level.
</P>
<P>
The local private sector has expanded its business range from
commerce, trade, catering and services to the industrial,
construction, transportation, real estate, consulting,
pharmaceutical and education sectors.
</P>
<P>
The city has 13,500 self-employed people engaged in the
processing sector, 250 in scientific and technological areas and
52 in export businesses.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses account for 7.8 percent of local tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses have promoted the implementation of reforms
in local state enterprises by providing jobs for the growing
number of unemployed and surplus workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
