<HEADLINE> Japan's LDP to Elect President on Friday Afternoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Liberal Democratic Party's
election for the next president will be on Friday in the
auditorium of LDP headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The results of the first vote are scheduled to be announced at
around 14:50 local time (0550 GMT). If there is a winner, he will
immediately make a brief speech to party members and then hold a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
If there is no majority, the first and second place candidates
go straight into a runoff. A winner of the runoff is likely to be
declared, and he will make a brief speech to the party and then
hold a news conference at around 17:00 local time.
</P>
<P>
There are 414 people who will vote in the election -- 263 LDP
lower house members, 104 LDP upper house members and 47 LDP
provincial representatives. A majority of 208 is needed.
</P>
<P>
Provincial representatives can either deliver their votes in
person or vote by absentee ballot.
</P>
<P>
Parliament is expected to designate a new prime minister on
July 30.
</P>
<P>
Former Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama, Health and
Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi and Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi are competing for the post.
</P>
<P>
Among the three competitors, Obuchi is thought to be the most
promising candidate for the next LDP president.
</P>
<P>
Jiji Press said Obuchi will cancel his planned trip for the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) Regional Forum in
Manila on Monday, since he is anticipating a victory and is now
busy preparing a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Of the parliament members, 91 belong to the Obuchi faction, 87
to the Mitsuzuka faction, 83 to the Miyazawa faction, 62 to the
former Watanabe faction and 17 to the former Komoto
faction. Others do not belong to any faction.
</P>
<P>
The LDP president is almost certain to become the next prime
minister to replace Ryutaro Hashimoto because the party holds a
majority in the more powerful lower house of parliament. Under
Japan's constitution, the winner of the lower house vote for prime
minister becomes the premier even if the upper house selects a
different person.
</P>
<P>
Japanese stocks opened lower Friday morning before the LDP
presidency voting began. The key Nikkei stock average fell 49.55
points, or 0.3 percent, to 16,138.46 in the first 15 minutes of
trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
