<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paralyzed Chinese Gymnast Able to Extend Her Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Sang Lan, a 17-year-old Chinese
gymnast, was able to flex her elbows and extend her arms this
evening, but still had no feeling below her uper chest and was
unlikely to walk again.
</P>
<P>
Sang, who suffered a severe spinal injury while performing a
routine warm-up vault at the Goodwill Games Tuesday night,
remained in guarded condition, according to doctor Vincent Leone,
an orthopedic spinal surgeon who treated the gymnast at the Nassau
County Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
Doctors realigned her spinal cord and began treatment with
corticosteroids Tuesday night, Leone said. He told the press that
treatment was expected to begin with an experimental drug in an
attempt to regenerate damaged nerves.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Dawei, a doctor of the medical center who is acting as the
interpreter for Sang, told Xinhua that the surgery plan had
already worked out, and the operation date was settled for
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Sang's parents will arrive here Friday night, but Zhao Yuxin,
leader of the Chinese gymnastics team, had gotten the approvement
from Sang's parents to sign her name on the surgery form at the
medical center. That means the surgery can be carried out before
the arrival of Sang's parents.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, a post picture has been put on the wall of
Sang's room. All the gymnasts attending the Games have signed
their names and prayers for Sang.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't see Sang weep or cry these days," Zhou said. "The
first question she asked when she saw team leader Zhao was 'Can I
return to competitions in future?'"
</P>
<P>
Sang is the only child for her parents, who are ordinary
workers in a small city with a total monthly earning about 150
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese gymnastics team, Sang has received
some financial donations in the past two days from American
people. "We are so grateful for what American people have done for
Sang Lan," exclaimed Zhao. She also told Xinhua that Sang will
remain at the medical center to receive further treatment after
the Games.
</P>
<P>
Leone said Sang will undergo surgery to fuse her damaged
vertebrae and implant metal stabilizers. He called her injury
"devastating" and "violent", and said it was too early to give an
accurate prognosis about Sang's future.
</P>
<P>
While he said that some improvement could be expected in her
upper extremities, he added: "I really can't comment on her lower
extremities."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he thought Sang would be able to walk eventually,
Leone said: "You'd be surprised. I'm still going to say unlikely,
but I'm very optimistic."
</P>
<P>
Sang's catastrophic injury again raised questions about the
safety of gymnastics, and of the vault in particular. In the past
decade, the aparatus has produced three injuries that have left
gymnasts paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
Julissa Gomez, an American, broke her neck while attempting a ba
ckward handspring on the horse in 1988, and died from
complications three years later.
</P>
<P>
Adriana Duffy, who competed for Puerto Rico, was confined to
wheelchair after 1989 vaulting accident.
</P>
<P>
Another catastrophic gymnastics injury was suffered by Elena
Moukina, the 1978 world all-around champion from the former Soviet
Union, who was paralyzed in 1980 after an accident during a
tumbling routine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
