<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's exports to Asian countries during the
first half of this year registered a drop of 20 percent compared
to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
It was officially reported that Brazilian exports to Asia in
the first six months of this year amounted to 2.923 billion
dollars, while those of last year were 3.672 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay has received a total investment of 555
million U.S. dollars for the construction of tourism complexes
since 1995 when it announced several incentives for the sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tourism Ministry, fifteen tourism projects
worth 25.5 million dollars have been approved during the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's exports during the first half of this
year amounted to 2.514 billion dollars, which represents a 19.65
percent increase against the 2.101 billion dollars registered
during the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Foreign Trade Ministry show that 1.421 billion
dollars of the total exports were industrial products; 869 million
dollars were agriculture products, and 222.64 million dollars were
livestock and fishing products.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean motor vehicle output was 11,475 units in
the first half of this year, a 6.3 percent drop compared to the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Motor Vehicle Commission of the Production
Promotion Corporation show that production was led by General
Motors, which assembled 8,936 units, followed by Automotors
Franco Chilena, 1,188 units, and Cormecanica, 625 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
