<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smith to Appear for FINA Doping Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Irish swimmer Michelle Smith could
be punished for a lifetime ban should she was to be convicted of
tampering with a urine sample in the hearing to be conducted in
Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Smith, winner of three gold medals at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics, would appear at a hearing on Friday before a doping panel
of the FINA, swimming's world governing body, her lawyer Peter
Lennon confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Smith was charged of manipulating an out-of-competition drug
test in Ireland on January 10 by adulterating her sample with
alcohol, but she has consistently denied taking drugs to boost her
performance.
</P>
<P>
In April, FINA said Smith's samples, tested at an
IOC-accredited laboratory in Barcelona, Spain, showed "unequivocal
signs of adulteration" and "physical manipulation."
</P>
<P>
Both samples reportedly contained a lethal concentration of
alcohol, indicating that the offender intended to avoid the
possible detection of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Under FINA rules, tampering with a urine sample is considered
as serious as taking steroids. The maximum penalty is a life ban.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear how long Smith's hearing will last, or when FINA
will announce its verdict.
</P>
<P>
Smith has faced strings of doping allegations ever since she
won three gold medals at the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
