<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's B-Share Trading Bearish In First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- In the first half of this year,
B-share trading on both the Shanghai Stock Exchange and the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange remained sluggish because of poor
performances of B-share issues generally, and the uncertain
international economic situation.
</P>
<P>
B-shares are sold only to overseas investors, while A-shares
are designed for domestic buyers.
</P>
<P>
Both the Shanghai and Shenzhen B-share indicators fell to
all-time lows, at 38.40 points and 551 points, respectively, and
have been fluctuating since the early months of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the number of B-share-issuing companies
listed on China's two exchanges stood at 112, including five new
issuers who floated B-shares in the first six months this year.
</P>
<P>
Local observers attribute the current B-share difficulties
partly to the collapse of Yamaichi Securities Co. and the Hong
Kong-based Peregrine Brokerage Ltd., two major underwriters of
Chinese B-shares.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the withdrawal of foreign capital from Asia and the
active selling of B-shares by foreign investors have worsened the
situation.
</P>
<P>
However, the sluggish B-share market has been caused mainly by
the poor performances of B-shares overall, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
They forecast that B-share trading will not recover from its
current downward trend soon, because the end of Asia's financial
turmoil is not in sight.
</P>
<P>
But the experts do not rule out the possibility of a rebound in
B-share trading, since the authorities are paying greater
attention to the issue, and have adopted a series of measures to
standardize and stimulate the operation of the securities
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Province Bids Farewell to Blackout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Limitations on electricity
consumption have become history in southwest China's Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
"The issue now is how to encourage people and businesses to use
more electricity," said Zou Guangyan, vice governor of Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this month, power consumption quotas and the sale of
large consumption rights are obsolete terms, and blackouts no
longer bother people during the nights. Consumers also are no
longer charged for owning air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
Aside from ending power-consumption limits, the provincial
government also is now committed to speeding up construction of
power grids, cutting power prices and improving after-sales
services.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan was a province with one of the worst electricity
shortages in China, despite accounting for one-third of the
nation's hydropower resources.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the construction of a number of power projects, the
power supply of the province now exceeds demand.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, according to official estimates, the
province's total generating capacity will reach 12 million
kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is working to promote electricity
consumption, the vice governor said.
</P>
<P>
For example, urban households with a monthly consumption of 150
kwh and rural households with a monthly consumption of 80 kwh
will enjoy a 10 percent discount.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
