<HEADLINE> 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting to Open in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers from the nine
member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) will gather here Friday to discuss a number of issues
affecting the region.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM), the
ministers will discuss the ongoing Asian financial crisis and
measures to deal with its social impacts, the forthcoming
Cambodian elections, nuclear proliferation in South Asia, fight
against transnational crimes and other important issues.
</P>
<P>
The AMM is an annual event responsible for the formulation of
policy guidelines and coordination of ASEAN activities.
</P>
<P>
At this year's meeting, the ministers are also expected to
discuss and decide whether there will be a change in ASEAN's
policy from "non-interference" to "flexible engagement."
</P>
<P>
Thailand raised the idea of "flexible engagement," which means
that when domestic developments in a country have had positive or
adverse effects on other ASEAN nations, these nations can give
advice to or press the said country to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, ASEAN's rotating chairman this year, supports
the new proposal. However, all the other ASEAN members -- Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Singapore and Vietnam -- are
opposed to the idea. Analysts expect that no consensus will be
reached at the AMM.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will sign the Second Protocol of the Treaty of
Amity and Cooperation which will include Papua New Guinea and a
joint declaration which aims to build Southeast Asia into a region
free from drug production, abuse and trafficking by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are also supposed to issue a statement on the
Asian financial crisis, which has lasted for a year and crippled
almost all the economies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada will deliver a keynote
speech at the opening ceremony of the 31st ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the Fifth ASEAN Regional Forum and the ASEAN
Post-Ministerial Conferences will also take place here.
</P>
<P>
During the two ensuing events, ASEAN nations will exchange
views on political and security issues with its 10 dialogue
partners (Australia, Canada, China, the European Union, India,
Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Russia and the United States) and
the two observers Cambodia and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
To make preparations for the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting,
the ASEAN Standing Committee meeting and the ASEAN Senior
Officials Meeting were already held here on July 21 to 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
