<HEADLINE> BNFL Inc. Wins Massive US Nuclear Clean-up Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- British Nuclear Fuels (BNFL) has
won a 20-year clear-up deal worth up to 6.9 billion U.S. dollars
from the American government.
</P>
<P>
An official from BNFL's American subsidiary, BNFL Inc. said
Thursday that the contract involves the removal of radioactivity
from millions of gallons of waste stored in underground tanks at
the Hanford Site near Richland, Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two part contract will result in the safe treatment of
about 10 percent of the waste (equal to 20 to 25 percent of the
radioactivity) in Hanford's 54 million gallons of waste by 2018.
</P>
<P>
The company's American subsidiary has won almost 2.5 billion
dollars worth of nuclear clear-up business in the U.S. since being
established in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In the latest contract the British company has Bechte, GTS
Duratek and Science Applications International as partners.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Crimmins, BNFL Inc. President and Chief Executive
Officer said: "The agreement marks a vitally important step on the
path to a safe, efficient, and timely clear-up of Hanford's tank
waste."
</P>
<P>
"We are confident the overall approach is the right one and
will protect the environment by converting liquid radioactive
waste into a stable glass form for ultimate disposal," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
