<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Plunge Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street Stocks plunged nearly
200 points Thursday as U.S. aircraft maker Boeing joined a sudden
chorus of major companies with discouraging earning news in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The leading Dow Jones industrial average fell 195.93 to
8,932.98, about 400 points below last Friday's record close of
9,337.97 and its first finish below 9,000 since July 1.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also suffered heavy losses, with
declining issues outnumbering advancers by nearly a 4-to-1 margin
in heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-company index, a model against
which many stock mutual funds are pattened or compared, fell
24.33 to 1,139.75, down about 4 percent from last Friday's
closing record of 1,186.75.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index, dominated by technology leaders
like Microsoft, fell 34.53 to 1,935.22. It was the third
straight losing session after a streak of nine straight closing
records for the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
The main factor behind this week's downturn has been the sudden
revelation of earning troubles at very prominent companies,
including Dow components Merck, Hewlett-Packard and DuPont.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's discouraging profit news gave a another heavy blow to
the investors. The Seattle-based aircraft giant failed to
satisfy Wall Street's deflated expectations for second-quarter
profits and issued disappointing forecasts for the full year and
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
