<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Harshly Criticizes U.S. Official Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece Thursday harshly criticized
the statements made by U.S. official on the Cyprus problem, saying
they were unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements by White House spokesman Mike Mccurry
that the Cyprus problem issue was a problem of "conflict" between
the two communities in the divided island, Greek spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that the Cyprus problem was one of invasion
and occupation of a large part of the island republic by the
Turkish army.
</P>
<P>
He continued that this was what is being accepted by the
international community, and it constitutes the basis of the
United Nations resolutions and its framework for a settlement of
the problem.
</P>
<P>
If there was a conflict, it was between the rational and
irrational, justice and lawlessness, legality and tyranny, he
said, adding that the Greek government wanted to believe that the
United States did not wish to take the place of the United Nations
or to monopolize the international community's interest in efforts
to settle the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos also expressed his
dissatisfaction over Washington's position towards the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. President Bill Clinton had made several
promises during his pre-election campaigns concerning a solution
to the 24-year Cyprus problem, none of which had today been
fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos also
criticized Washington for its pressures to cancel the deployment
of the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles by Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
