<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Mideast Peace Process Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Thursday that he did not think the Middle East peace
process was over and the United States would keep working to push
it forward.
</P>
<P>
"If I thought the process were over, I would say it was
over," Clinton told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"We have continued intense negotiations (between Israel and
the Palestinians) to this day with both sides based on the ideas
we advanced early," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we come to a time when we think it's hopeless, I'llsay
it's hopeless. Right now I am not prepared to say that," Clinton
said. "I think there is still a chance we can get an agreement
and I am going to keep working on it."
</P>
<P>
Clinton acknowledged differences remain between Israel and
the Palestinians and the peace process still is deadlocked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
