<DOCNO> XIE19980724.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned over Iran's Medium-Range Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Thursday
showed profound concerns over Iran's test-firing of a
medium-range missile.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said the missile could change the
"stability dynamics" or the Middle East if Iran made it
operational.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian missile, known as a new model of Shehab-3, launched
on Tuesday night, has a range of about 800 miles (1,300km), which
could cover all of Israel, Saudi Arabia and part of Turkey. A U.S.
official said that "It puts U.S. forces in the region at risk."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said it was "a source of
concern to us that they are pursuing a program of this nature."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would like to discuss the matter with Iranian
President Mohammed Khatami, if a dialogue opens.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters once the
Shehab-3 missile is made operational, "Iran will have the
ability to strike more distant targets -- including Israel,
portions of Russia, Turkey and Saudi Arabia."
</P>
<P>
"At that point it would have an impact strategically," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the Pentagon,spokesman Ken Bacon said the missile was
clearly not meant only for Iraq, Iran's enemy in the long Gulf
War of the 1980s, when both sides used Scud missiles.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States expects other Shehab missile tests
soon because one alone would not be enough to make Iran
confident that the missile would work.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the Iranian missile test would make the United
States keep working on a system to offset any possible missile
attacks.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say if either Patriot 3 missiles or the
Arrow missiles the United States is developing with Israel would
be able to shoot down an Iranian missile.  
</P>
</TEXT>
