<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Asks Iraq to Hand over Disputed Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler Thursday requested Iraq to cooperate with
his inspection commission and hand over documents on munitions
used by Iraq in its 1980-1988 war with Iran.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. Security Council, Butler complained
that Iraq refused to hand over the document, saying that the
refusal was a violation of U.N. resolutions on access to
weapons-related materials.
</P>
<P>
Butler's complaint to the Security Council was the first about
field inspections in Iraq since U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
signed an agreement in Baghdad in February, giving the U.N.
inspectors full access to potential weapons sites and related
materials in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.N. inspectors said that the disputed documents were needed to
determine what munitions in Iraq's possession had been expanded so
the commission could verify if any still remained.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that these types of munitions had been declared
earlier by Iraq to have been used for chemical and biological
warfare agent delivery. But arms officials said that they had no
proof Iraq had used biological arms against Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspectors are responsible for ridding Iraq of all
weapons of mass destruction. U.N. sanctions against Iraq imposed
eight years ago can not be lifted until the inspectors have
accounted for all dangerous arms and related materials although
Iraq has repeatedly denied that it still has any banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
Current Security Council President Sergei Lavrov of Russia
intends to ask Iraq's U.N. Ambassador Nizar Hamdoon to explain the
incident to the Council, sources close to the Council said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq reportedly said that the disputed documents would be
opened when Butler meets Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Taraq Aziz
in Baghdad on August 2.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
